<FIRST>u i BC-Obit-HuYaobang 1stLd-Writethru   04-15 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Obit-Hu Yaobang, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0826,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Head Of Chinese Communist Party Dead At 74</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with biographic details, quotes,
survivors. No pickup. Edits to trim and conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hu Yaobang, head of China's Communist Party from
1980 until he was ousted in disgrace in 1987, died Saturday after
suffering a heart attack. He was 74.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Hu suffered a heart attack
on April 8 from which he never recovered. The news agency said Hu
died of extensive cardiac infarction, an obstruction of blood
vessels, at 7:53 a.m. Saturday (7:53 p.m. Friday EDT).
   According to the South China Morning Post daily newspaper of
Hong Kong, Hu suffered the heart attack during a meeting last
Saturday of the Communist Party Politburo, the party's top
decision-making body.
   Hu, although retaining his seat in the 17-member Politburo, made
few official appearances and had become a nearly forgotten figure
in Chinese politics after his dramatic ouster in January 1987.
   Hu survived 10 years of political purgatory to emerge as head of
the 47-million member Communist Party, but then was purged again as
he stood on the brink of becoming China's most powerful man.
   Hu was one of China's most outspoken critics of the leftist
excesses of Mao Tse-tung's 1966-76 Cultural Revolution that
banished him to exile, and became a leading pragmatist in
encouraging a more market-oriented economy and greater private
initiative.
   It was his tendency to speak out in a nation where private
opinions are discouraged, and his tolerance toward critics of the
socialist system, that led to his ouster as party general secretary
in 1987, at the height of the campaign against ``bourgeois
liberalization.''
   Despite charges that he had permitted Westernization and
pro-capitalist sentiments in China, Hu was a dedicated nationalist
and party member. He joined the Communist guerrilla forces at age
14 and never left a doubt that party ideals took precedence over
everything, including personal and press freedoms.
   Hu became head of the Communist Party in February 1980, and was
allied closely to senior leader Deng Xiaoping, whom he first met in
1941. The longtime bridge partners shared the conviction that
China, in order to escape the grinding poverty of the past and grow
economically, must not repeat the political upheavals that marked
the communists' first quarter-century in power.
   It was widely believed that Hu was in line to take over some of
Deng's functions, including head of the party's powerful Central
Military Commission, when Deng finally left the scene.
   However, Hu had long alienated some conservatives with his blunt
criticisms of Mao's policies and the military reportedly hedged its
support for a man who had never held a senior military position.
   In the end, Deng, reportedly angered when Hu on several
occasions bypassed his orders or made decisions without consulting
other party leaders, is believed to have played a key role in
engineering Hu's ``resignation.''
   Hu in particular was blamed for allowing an atmosphere that
resulted in widespread pro-democracy student demonstrations in
December 1986.
   Hu was born in 1915 in Liuyang County, Hunan Province, 72 miles
from the birthplace of Mao.
   Like Deng and others who later rose to the top echelons of the
party, Hu took part in the Long March of 1934-35. He was a party
official in Sichuan Province when the communists drove the
Nationalist government to Taiwan and took over power in 1949.
   In 1952 he became secretary of the Communist Youth League, and
four years later joined the party's Central Committee.
   In 1966, as head of the Youth League, Hu became a prime target
of Mao's Cultural Revolution. Red Guards shaved his head, forced
him to crawl on his hands and knees in an act of public humiliation
and sent him to rural Henan Province for 2{ years.
   Among his alleged sins, the leftists charged Hu and Deng, who
was also banished to the countryside, used railroad cars and
special airplanes to ferry bridge partners around the country.
   After Henan, Hu underwent another two years being
``re-educated'' and five years under house arrest. In 1975 he
resurfaced as an official of the Academy of Sciences.
   In 1977 Hu became head of the party's Organization Department,
where he supervised the redress of frame-ups during the Cultural
Revolution.
   By 1980, Hu was elected secretary-general of the party Central
Committee, and served as party chairman, the post once held by Mao,
until the title was abolished in 1982.
   Hu was 5-foot, 3-inches, slightly taller than Deng, and like
Deng, a heavy smoker.
   In 1983 he revealed he had four children and five grandchildren.
His wife was reported to be a retired textile factory manager.
</TEXT>
