<FIRST>r a PM-DukakisSlide Bjt   04-15 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis Slide, Bjt,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remember Mike Dukakis? In Massachusetts They Do, And Not Fondly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few days after Michael Dukakis lost the
presidential election, a London wax museum yanked a model of the
defeated candidate from public view. It was the shortest exhibition
in the museum's history.
   At home, Gov. Dukakis is still on display most days at the
Statehouse, but critics, and even some supporters, suggest he has
become something of an invisible figure.
   It's been a long, hard winter for Dukakis. He has announced a
deficit in the state budget, made himself a lame duck, proposed $1
billion in new spending, asked taxpayers to cover the shortfall,
and taken a dive in public opinion polls.
   He has also seen his wife, Kitty, through a monthlong
residential treatment program for alcoholism.
   April is proving to be another cruel month. Massachusetts is
facing a water shortage, Dukakis' mother has been in the hospital,
and members of his own party are writing him off as irrelevant.
   One legislative leader emerged from a budget-crisis meeting in
Dukakis' office last week and told reporters that taxes weren't
mentioned and neither was the ``L-word.'' When reporters asked
which L-word he had in mind, the leader said, ``Loser.''
   Through it all, Dukakis has chugged along in the slow-but-sure
style that marked his campaign, leaving his shrinking circle of
admirers to marvel at his steadiness and giving his critics more
reason to believe _ as Ted Koppel said _ that he just doesn't get
it.
   After more than a quarter-century in public life, Dukakis
himself takes a long view.
   ``Steady as she goes,'' Dukakis said when asked about the
state's multiple problems.
   ``He seems to have the attitude that this too shall pass,''
observed state Rep. Nicholas Paleologos, a fellow Greek and fellow
Democrat who was one of Dukakis' staunchest supporters.
   ``He's clicked off of the presidential campaign, and he's
clicked back onto being governor. He burns at about the same
temperature no matter what he does,'' Paleologos said.
   ``He really has become a non-entity, at the Statehouse,''
commented Barbara Anderson, the leader of Citizens for Limited
Taxation, who shoveled anti-Dukakis ammunition to the Bush forces
last year.
   Democratic state Rep. William Galvin traced the governor's slump
to two events that followed Dukakis' acknowledgment in December
that the state was $600 million short on a $12 billion budget.
   Galvin said Dukakis lost public support with his $735 million
tax plan and lost legislative support when he ruled out another run
for governor in 1990.
   ``A year ago, not only was he governor, he was a governor who
might be president,'' the Boston Democrat said, adding that
lame-duck status diminishes any politician's authority, ``whether
they're president or governor or sewer commissioner.''
   On the national scene, Dukakis nearly vanished as quickly as the
London waxworks display, which was on view for only 40 days.
   Two weekends ago, when many prominent politicians were in
Washington for a mammoth pro-choice rally, Dukakis was in New York
City for a Greek Independence Day parade, and he barely made a
ripple.
   The Democrats' new national chairman, Ron Brown, was in Boston
recently and told a luncheon of politicians and contributors that
the Democrats are in great shape except for presidential politics.
As guests nodded, Brown said the problem in 1988 was a slow-footed
campaign that lacked a message and let the Republicans define the
terms.
   Dukakis was sitting about 10 feet away.
   Statewide poll results in early February had the governor's
favorability rating down from his usual range in 70s to 43.5
percent and his unfavorable rating at an all-time high of 52.7
percent.
   Still, the governor's top aides and close friends insist that
things will work out.
   Paul Brountas, the governor's oldest friend, who chaired the
presidential campaign, had lunch with Dukakis recently.
   ``I think he's in great shape,'' Brountas said. ``People get
angry at their basketball team if they lose in the finals. They
don't treat them so badly if they lose in the semi-finals. It's
like any loss. People are disappointed.''
</TEXT>
