<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 0429EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ElizabethLayoffs     04-15 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elizabeth Layoffs,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Workers Protest Layoffs, Call For Ouster Of Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharp cutbacks in this city's police
force and fire department because of budget problems have prompted
calls for the removal of Mayor Thomas Dunn, who has held office for
a quarter-century.
   About 250 police officers, firefighters and ambulance personnel
protested for a fourth straight day Friday, chanting on City Hall
steps, ``Dunn Must Go,'' and ``The roof, the roof, the roof's on
fire, let that ... burn.''
   Elizabeth, population 106,000, laid off 93 civilian employees,
70 police officers, 53 firefighters and 12 emergency medical
technicians at 6 p.m. Friday.
   The cuts mean a 22 percent reduction in the police force and 20
percent reduction in the fire department, along with the closing of
two firehouses and four of 11 fire companies, said Tony Valvano,
vice president of the Fireman's Mutual Benevolent Association in
Elizabeth.
   ``We've supported the mayor right down the line,'' Valvano said.
``We've done everything possible to help him but he's done nothing
to help us.''
   Dunn's term is up in 1992. The Democrat postponed for 45 days
the layoffs of 169 other employees scheduled to lose their jobs.
   The mayor has blamed Assembly Speaker Chuck Hardwick of Union
for the city's budget shortfall. Hardwick, a Republican
gubernatorial candidate, said a funding source is needed before he
would allow an Assembly vote to bring money to distressed cities.
   Hardwick criticized Dunn, calling the layoffs ``a shameful
political stunt that unnecessarily jeopardizes public safety.''
   Dunn called Hardwick ``hard-headed,'' and blamed the budget
problems on garbage disposal costs for the city adjacent to New
York's Staten Island. Costs have tripled in the last year because
of environmental laws that force the city to ship its trash out of
state.
   Elizabeth received $7.1 million from the state's aid to
distressed cities program, a 30 percent cut from last year. It had
requested $33.7 million.
   Valvano said the police and firefighters blame Hardwick, but
think Dunn is overreacting to the budget problems.
   ``The money is there, but he's just not using it,'' Valvano
said. ``We're not saying the city isn't in a fiscal crisis, it
probably is. But this doesn't have to happen right now. We feel
like Mayor Dunn has jumped the gun.''
   The City Council earlier this week approved a measure to
transfer funds earmarked for garbage disposal costs to pay the
employees for at least another month. Dunn rejected the move,
saying it broke state law.
</TEXT>
