<FIRST>r i PM-China-Abortion     04-15 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Abortion,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Had 32 Million Abortions From 1985-87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One out of every three pregnancies in China ends
in abortion, and 32 million abortions were carried out from 1985 to
1987, an official daily said today.
   The English-language China Daily, quoting earlier reports in the
Chinese press, also said 80 percent of abortions were requested by
women who did not know how to use contraceptives or whose
contraceptive methods failed.
   The daily said 70 percent of Chinese women of child-bearing age
use contraception, but 56 million do not.
   The report came out one day after China marked the birth of its
1.1 billionth citizen. The government has used the new population
figure to warn that the nation's family planning policies are being
ignored and China faces severe food and housing shortages if
population growth is not controlled.
   China denies foreign charges of forced abortions for women who
violate the one child per family policy or become pregnant without
authorization from their local family planning office.
   Last year the State Planning Commission said there were 10.39
million abortions in 1987, or 46 for every 100 live births. In the
United States, the abortion rate is approximately one for every
three live births.
   The daily said that of all contraceptive users, 40 percent are
women using intrauterine devices and 38 percent are women who have
been sterilized. Another 11 percent are men who have had
vasectomies, 5 percent are women taking contraceptive pills and 3
percent are men who use condoms.
   Chinese-made IUDs are reportedly of low quality, and the report
said 40 percent of women who use IUDS get pregnant.
</TEXT>
