<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil-Mansion     04-15 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Mansion,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rich Family Fighting Marxist Mayor's Move To Expropiate Mansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marxist mayor of Sao Paulo is
battling one of Brazil's richest families in a drive to turn its
mansion, a symbol of Brazilian excess, into a workers' museum.
   Mayor Luiza Erundina signed an order Tuesday to expropriate the
huge neo-classical mansion of the Matarazzo family, believed to be
Brazil's most valuable private piece of urban real estate _ worth
an estimated $120-150 million.
   The mayor, a member of the socialist-oriented Workers Party,
said she wants to convert the mansion into a Workers' Museum and
Cultural Center.
   But a lawyer for the Matarazzos said the family would fight the
decision ``to the end.''
   The 47,000-square-foot white stone mansion, with vast gardens
and servants quarters in the rear, sits on a 3-acre wooded lot on
Avenida Paulista, in the heart of Brazil's most important financial
center.
   The house was built in 1941 by Count Francesco Matarazzo, an
Italian immigrant who became an industrialist and one of the
country's richest men. It was designed by Marcello Piacentini, the
official architect of Italian fascist leader Benito Mussolini.
   Today, surrounded by skyscrapers and fast-food restaurants, the
Matarazzo mansion is a reminder of a bygone age, when Avenida
Paulista was lined by elegant estates belonging to the cream of Sao
Paulo society.
   The count's heirs want to demolish the house and sell the
property, but they can't if the government expropriates it.
   The mayor's chief of staff, Jose Eduardo Cardoso, said in a
telephone interview that, ``We have only just begun the
expropriation process, and according to law we have five years to
conclude it. If by 1994 the expropriation is not completed it can
no longer be carried out.''
   Cardoso said the Matarazzo property is valued at $120-150
million, ``which we will have to pay to finalize the
expropriation.''
   He said the city will try to get funds from private companies to
pay for the expropriation, ``because obviously the municipal
government does not have the money for this kind of thing.''
   Matarazzo lawyer Magalhaes said the money could ``pay for at
least 30,000 low income houses, or 10 large hospitals or hundreds
of day care centers, endeavors which would be much more in line
with a government that claims to be concerned with the well-being
of the poor.''
   After her election last Nov. 15, Erundina said she would change
the priorities of past city governments and concentrate on health,
housing and educational projects for the poor.
</TEXT>
