<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 0537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-China     04-15 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Calls For Two Governments, One China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it may scrap its
40-year vow to reconquer mainland China if Beijing recognizes
Nationalist sovereignty over Taiwan.
   Justice Minister Hsiao Tien-tzang told the Legislative Yuan on
Friday that China must approve a ``one China, two governments''
formula being promoted by the Nationalists to help the eventual
reunification of the mainland and Taiwan.
   ``Whether we continue to fight the Communist rebels depends on
the response from the other side of the Taiwan Straits,'' Hsiao
said, according to a statement issued today by the assembly.
   Taiwan newspapers, in dispatches from Tokyo, said Chinese
Premier Li Peng, who is visiting Japan, rejected the Nationalists'
suggestion on Friday because it would require Beijing to drop its
one-China policy.
   The decree calling for the reconquering of the mainland was
imposed in 1949 after the Nationalists lost a civil war on the
mainland and fled to Taiwan.
   Hsiao's statement was in reply to demands by Huang Huang-hsiung,
a member of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party, to abolish
the emergency decree.
   Huang said the Nationalist government ``has in fact recognized
Communist Chinese sovereignty over the people on the mainland'' by
pursuing a more flexible policy toward China since last year.
   For the past four decades, both the Nationalists and Communists
have maintained that Taiwan is a Chinese province and that
reunification will come under one government.
   In 1987, the Nationalists ended 38 years of martial law to allow
the formation of new opposition parties, but they retained the
emergency decree.
   As part of its flexible policy, Taiwan announced last week that
it will send an official delegation to China for the first time to
attend the annual meeting of the Asian Development Bank that begins
in Beijing on May 4.
   But it said the decision did not signal a change in its
anti-communist policy, and members of the delegation would not
discuss relations between the rival governments.
   The 12-member delegation is to be headed by Finance Minister
Shirley Kuo but will include Foreign Ministry officials.
   Government officials said Foreign Ministry representatives were
included to handle ``possible protocol problems'' and would not be
involved in diplomatic meetings with the Chinese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
