<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0432 04-15 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0432,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with Yaobang death; a separate moved on Yaobang as a0422.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Hu Yaobang</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hu Yaobang, the former head of China's Communist
Party who was swept from power in a 1987 purge, died today after a
heart attack, the official Xinhua News Agency said. He was 73.
   Despite frequent rumors that Hu would make a comeback with the
help of his former mentor Deng, Hu has been the forgotten man of
Chinese politics since his ouster.
   Hu was last seen in public at the annual session of China's
parliament, which concluded April 4.
   Hu became head of the 47 million-member Communist Party in 1980.
Together with Deng and then-Premier Zhao Ziyang, he was
instrumental in initiating the market-style reforms that have
brought prosperity to millions of Chinese.
   Hu's outspoken manner led to his persecution during the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution and may in the end have alienated Deng to the
point where he authorized Hu's 1987 ``resignation.''
   Hu stepped down after taking the blame for pro-democracy student
demonstrations that swept the nation in December 1986. Hu was
allowed to retain his seat in the 17-member Politburo, the main
decision-making body in the party.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Philip Furlong</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip J. Furlong, the oldest Roman Catholic
bishop in the United States, died Thursday at the age of 96.
   Furlong was ordained in 1918. He became president of Cathedral
College in 1938 and held that post until 1941.
   In 1941, Furlong was named monsignor with the title of papal
chamberlain. In 1945, he was named a domestic prelate and was made
secretary of education for the Archdiocese of New York.
   Five years later, he became pastor of St. Thomas More parish in
Manhattan, and was elevated to prothonotary apostolic. In 1956, he
was ordained an auxiliary bishop. He remained as pastor of St.
Thomas More and an auxiliary to the military vicar until his
retirement in 1969.
   Furlong also served as national Catholic chaplain of the Civil
Air Patrol from 1942 to 1945 and national chaplain for the Girl
Scouts from 1946 to 1955.
</TEXT>
