<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 0803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Congress     04-15 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Congress,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Soviet Parliament To Meet May 25</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Congress of People's Deputies, the Soviet
Union's new parliamentary body, will go into session for the first
time on May 25, the Tass news agency said today.
   Tass said the date was announced in a decree of the Supreme
Soviet that was signed by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The congress must meet within two months of being elected.
   Nationwide multicandidate elections for 1,500 seats in the
congress were held March 26, and run-off elections were held on
April 9.
   But 199 of those seats remain unfilled. In those districts only
one or two candidates ran March 26 and voters refused to give
either of them a majority.
   New elections are being organized and balloting will take place
May 14 in those districts.
   Voters rejected dozens of top-ranking Communist Party and
government officials in the first nationwide multicandidate
balloting in 70 years.
   Another 750 members of the congress are being chosen from the
party, its affiliates, and social and professional organizations.
   The 2,250-deputy Congress will meet once a year. It will choose
the Soviet president and from among its members a new, more
powerful Supreme Soviet.
</TEXT>
