<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     04-15 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>See What You've Done, Priest Tells IRA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARRENPOINT, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest
presiding at the funeral of a 20-year-old woman today challenged
the Irish Republican Army to come back to the town and consider its
work.
   ``Ask yourselves if you have any justification for what you have
done?'' the Rev. Edward Hamill said at the funeral of Joanne
Reilly, a Roman Catholic killed by an IRA bomb.
   ``We ask God to enlighten the minds of those who have caused
this tragedy and this death, that they may see that they have no
cause to justify what happened,'' he told hundreds of mourners at
St. Peter's Catholic Church.
   Loudspeakers were set up outside to accommodate the overflow
crowd.
   Miss Reilly was killed by the explosion of a car bomb on
Wednesday outside the police station in this port town in County
Down. The IRA, a mainly Roman Catholic organization fighting
British rule in the province, delivered four warnings _ all of them
after the explosion.
   The organization later expressed its ``sincere apologies'' for
killing Miss Reilly, who worked in a shop near the police station.
Thirty people, including six policemen, were also injured.
   On Friday night, hundreds of Catholics and Protestants attended
a special interdenominational rally in Warrenpoint to protest the
killing and the continuing campaign of terror.
   Miss Reilly was the 23rd person killed this year in sectarian
violence in the province.
</TEXT>
