<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 3rdLd-Writethru   04-15 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0441,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Evacuate Wounded From Besieged Christian Sector</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with higher death toll, one fatality
a lawmaker. Pickup graf 8 pvs `The spokesman...' TRIMS thereafter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French naval vessel evacuated wounded
from Christian east Beirut today and brought medicine to the
besieged sector, but Moslem leaders disagreed on whether to accept
the humanitarian aid.
   Syrian and Christian gunners dueled intermittently with mortars
and rockets in and around Beirut before dawn. Police said two
people, including a Christian lawmaker, were killed and four people
were wounded during the shelling of the once fashionable
neighborhood of Ashrafiyeh.
   Police identified the dead parliamentary member as 72-year-old
Abu Sharaf, a Maronite. He represented the Christian Kesrouan
province in Lebanon's unicameral parliament.
   ``A rocket slammed into Ashrafiyeh. Deputy Abu Sharaf rushed to
the balcony after hearing screams for help. Then a second rocket
exploded in the same area. Shrapnel cut through his neck, killing
him instantly,'' a police report said.
   The latest casualties raised the overall toll to 217 dead and
731 wounded in the six-week battle, the latest in the nation's
14-year civil war.
   Police said a Lebanese navy gunboat during the night ferried 14
badly wounded Christians to the La Rance, a French navy support
ship with extensive hospital facilities, from the Christian port of
Jounieh.
   A police spokesman said the vessel had dropped anchor in
Lebanese territorial waters 10 miles off Jounieh.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing rules,
said most of the wounded were suffering from ``severe burns. They
were hit during the Syrian shelling (in previous fighting).''
   Some of the wounded will be treated aboard the French ship, but
difficult cases will be flown to France via Cyprus, officials have
said.
   The police spokesman said France's minister for humanitarian
assistance, Bernard Kouchner, supervised the operation from the
port. France has strong ties with Lebanon, which it ruled from
World War I until 1943.
   The spokesman said the gunboat brought medicine back from the La
Rance for hospitals in the 310-square-mile enclave that is home to
about 1 million Christians who are under fire from Syrian and
allied forces.
   A Moslem official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Kouchner was trying to persuade acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss,
who heads the Moslem cabinet in Lebanon's dual government, to allow
a similar evacuation of wounded Moslems from Syrian-policed west
Beirut.
   Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, had welcomed the French humanitarian aid.
   But Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt, the public works minister in
Hoss' cabinet, is opposed to the French assistance, the official
said.
   He said Jumblatt wants the La Rance and the French oil tanker
Penhors to anchor at a port his party's militia runs in Jiyeh, 15
miles south of Beirut, to violate a blockade imposed by Gen. Michel
Aoun on militia-run ports.
   The Penhors is carrying a shipment of fuel oil badly needed by
power stations in Lebanon to keep them running.
   Aoun's blockade of the port in early March started the latest
round of fighting between his 20,000 Christian troops and the Druse
militias. The Syrians later joined the fighting on the Druse side.
The militia ports deflect an estimated $100 million in levies
collected annually by the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
