<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Lockerbie 1stLd-Writethru a0401 04-15 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Lockerbie, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0401,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Visit Crash Site, Despite Earlier Indication</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS four grafs to update with Lockerbie material.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0447 to include editor's note.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will go home from a NATO summit
in June without stopping in Lockerbie, Scotland, where a Pan Am
jumbo jet crashed after a bomb exploded on board last December.
   The White House announcement on Friday reverses a plan announced
the previous day by administration officials.
   The officials had said Thursday that Bush would visit Lockerbie
to thank the people there for pitching in on the search and
recovery effort for victims of the tragedy.
   However, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
Friday it was decided Bush would not go.
   ``It was an idea. We couldn't work it in,'' he said.
   The stop was planned for early June on the way back from a NATO
summit in Brussels and visits to Italy, England and West Germany.
   ``It was just decided that at the end of the trip, we didn't
have time,'' Fitzwater said. He said the stop ``had some visual
appeal _ nice little town but it would have delayed us by a day and
a half.''
   The crash of Flight 103 last Dec. 21 killed all 259 people on
board and 11 on the ground.
   In Lockerbie, the Rev. James Annand said today, ``I don't think
anybody is unduly worried one way or the other.''
   ``It would have been very nice, but if he has other commitments
I don't think anybody is particularly upset. When we heard of the
possiblity, it was full of `ifs' and `maybes', anyway,'' said
Annand, a Church of Scotland minister.
   Sir Hector Monro, Conservative member of Parliament for the
area, said it was ``a bit of a disappointment.''
   ``It is all a bit of a mystery. Everybody began to look forward
to it and we will be disappointed now that it appears the visit is
off. There's not much more one can say,'' Munro said.
</TEXT>
