<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 0932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Palestinians-Israel     04-15 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palestinians-Israel,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Bankers Propose Partial Israeli Withdrawal, Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian leaders told Egypt they would
accept elections in Israeli-occupied territories under
international supervision and after a partial Israeli pullback, an
Egyptian government source said today.
   The proposal came from West Bankers led by Faisal Husseini, head
of the Arab Studies Center in East Jerusalem, who met with Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Sunday, the source said.
   The proposals were ``ideas for consideration that do not amount
to a cut-and-dried plan,'' the source said on condition of
anonymity.
   They were a response to a peace plan proposed by Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir and unveiled on a trip to Washington
earlier this month, the source said.
   Shamir suggested Israeli-run elections be held in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip to choose representatives with whom Israel could
negotiate Palestinian autonomy.
   ``These local Palestinians are the people who are bearing the
brunt of the occupation. They are trying to help with ideas,
instead of rejecting things out of hand,'' the source said.
   PLO officials, who turned down the Shamir plan, indicated they
opposed the West Bankers' approach.
   Saeed Kamal, Cairo representative of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, denied that local Palestinians had offered any
proposals.
   ``This is a big lie,'' Kamal told The Associated Press.
   ``These so-called proposals are only ideas floated by Western
diplomats in Jerusalem. As far as the PLO is concerned, any
proposal involving elections can be made only in the U.S.-PLO
dialogue in Tunis,'' he said.
   Those talks began in the Tunisian capital in December after PLO
leader Yasser Arafat recognized Israel's right to exist, renounced
terrorism and accepted key U.N. resolutions on a Middle East
settlement.
   The Egyptian source said the West Bankers suggested a four-phase
plan.
   First, an international force would oversee withdrawal of
Israeli troops from populated areas in the occupied territories to
fringe positions.
   Polling then would be held under international supervision to
elect a parliament-in-exile. A delegation would be chosen from
among the parliament's members to negotiate interim self-rule with
the Israelis.
   In the final stage, the source said, the PLO and Israel would
negotiate autonomy for occupied territories at an international
conference.
   The PLO, however, demands that all Israeli forces leave the West
Bank and Gaza as a precursor to internationally-supervised
elections.
   At a meeting with President Bush last week, Shamir proposed his
plan for Israeli-overseen elections to choose Palestinians to
negotiate autonomy for the occupied territories.
   The Egyptian source said the Cairo government views the West
Bankers' ideas ``with an open mind. We have not taken any position
yet.''
   Since the uprising against Israel's occupation of the West Bank
and Gaza began in December 1987, more than 425 Palestinians and 18
Israelis have died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
