<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Cabinet     04-15 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Cabinet,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Names Powerful Defense Minister As Assistant President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak today named Defense
Minister Abdel-Halim Abu-Ghazala, who helped develop Egypt's strong
ties with the United States, to fill the vacant post of assistant
president.
   The position of assistant president has been largely ceremonial.
But Field Marshal Abu-Ghazala is viewed as the second most powerful
man in the government, and his appointment could represent a
stepping stone to the position of vice president.
   The country has had no vice president since Mubarak succeeded
assassinated President Anwar Sadat in October 1981. Mubarak served
as vice president to Sadat from 1975 until the assassination.
   The Defense Ministry, which Abu-Ghazala headed for eight years,
will now be operated by Maj. Gen. Youssef Sabry Abu-Taleb, who ran
Cairo's government for six years as governor.
   Mubarak announced the two appointments in decrees and
immediately swore in the two men to their new posts. No explicit
reason for the changes were given.
   Afterward, Prime Minister Atef Sedki told reporters only that
Mubarak ``needs at his side someone to help him in the huge tasks
that he has to discharge.'' He said he does not expect further
Cabinet changes.
   The last assistant president was former Prime Minister Mamdouh
Salem. He died three years ago, and the position has been vacant
since then.
   In the last few years, there have been frequent reports and
speculation that Mubarak would appoint Abu-Ghazala as vice
president. Abu-Ghazala denied the reports.
   Abu-Ghazala, 59, served as military attache in Washington
between 1976 and 1979. He was regarded as a prime player in forging
Cairo's special relationship with the United States after Egypt
signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979.
   He was graduated from Cairo's Military Academy in 1949, but he
later attended military courses both in the Soviet Union and the
United States. He was an officer in Egypt's 1956, 1967 and 1973
wars with Israel.
   Abu-Taleb, 60, served longer as Cairo's governor than anybody
else since Egypt became a republic in 1952. He is widely regarded
as the best governor modern Cairo ever had.
   The Middle East News Agency said his successor is Mahmoud
Sherif, governor of Sharkia province.
</TEXT>
