<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 0956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Obit-HuYaobang 1stLd-Writethru a0422 04-15 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Hu Yaobang, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0422,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hu Yaobang, Former Communist Party Leader, Dies At 73</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with official comment. TRIMS. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hu Yaobang, the former head of China's Communist
Party who was swept from power in a dramatic 1987 purge, died of
heart failure today. He was 73.
   Hu died exactly one week after suffering a heart attack during a
meeting of the Politburo, the party body which oversaw his downfall
two years before, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   The reformer once stood on the threshold of succeeding Deng
Xiaoping as the leader of China's 1.1 billion people, but he fell
from grace over 1986 pro-democracy student demonstrations.
   In a statement read on national television, the Communist Party
Central Committee praised Hu as a ``long-tested loyal communist
fighter, great proletarian revolutionary, statesman'' and
outstanding leader.
   A photo of Hu trimmed in black appeared on the screen before and
after the announcement while somber music played for about a minute.
   National television showed a film of Hu's trip to western China
in the early 1980s when he revisited sites he passed through during
the 1934-35 Long March, the Red Army's epic flight from Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalists.
   Xinhua carried a two-paragraph item with a short biography. The
People's Broadcasting Station mentioned his death in its regular
news briefs.
   Despite frequent rumors that Hu would make a comeback with the
help of his former mentor Deng, Hu has been the forgotten man of
Chinese politics since his ouster.
   Hu was last seen in public at the annual session of China's
parliament, the National People's Congress, which concluded April 4.
   Hu became head of the 47 million-member Communist Party in
February 1980. Together with Deng and then-Premier Zhao Ziyang, Hu
played an instrumental role in initiating the market-style economic
reforms that have brought prosperity to millions of Chinese.
   Hu, Deng's longtime bridge partner, was widely expected to take
over Deng's functions when China's senior leader, now 84, finally
stepped down.
   But he was always held in suspicion by China's conservative
factions, in part because of his blunt criticisms of Mao Tse-tung's
policies and his tendency to state his opinion without consulting
party members.
   In 1987 Hu stepped down as Communist Party secretary-general
after taking the blame for pro-democracy student demonstrations
that swept the nation in December 1986. He was allowed to retain
his seat in the 17-member Politburo.
   After Hu's ouster, Zhao moved over to take Hu's post as general
secretary of the party, and Li Peng, a technocrat with a more
cautious approach toward reform, was named premier.
   Hu was born in 1915 in Liuyang County, Hunan province, and,
according to official reports, left home at age 14 to join the
Communist Party Children's Corps.
   In 1952, three years after the communist takeover of the
mainland, he became secretary of the Communist Youth League and in
1956 joined the party Central Committee.
   In 1966, as head of the Youth League, he became a prime target
of Mao's Cultural Revolution. Red Guards shaved his head, forced
him to crawl on his hands and knees and sent him to rural Henan
province for 2{ years of exile.
   Among his alleged crimes was that he and Deng, another victim of
the leftists, used railroad cars and special airplanes to ferry
bridge partners around the country.
   After Henan, Hu underwent another two years of ``re-education''
and was under house arrest for five years. In 1975, he resurfaced
as an official of the Academy of Sciences, but in 1976 he was
branded a ``capitalist roader in the scientific front'' after
saying science and technology, not class struggle, is the
``locomotive of history.''
   In 1977, after the leftists were purged and Deng began his slow
rise to power, Hu took over as head of the party's Organization
Department, where he supervised the redress of frame-ups during the
Cultural Revolution.
   In 1980, he was elected secretary-general of the party Central
Committee, and served as chairman of the party, the post once held
by Mao, from 1981 until the title was abolished the next year. He
then became the party general secretary.
   In 1983, he revealed he had four children and five
grandchildren. His wife, Li Zhao, is a clothing designer and former
official in the Beijing Textile Bureau.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
