<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 2ndLd-Writethru   04-15 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0440,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Attack Kills 21 Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with another attack, 21 killed.
Pickup 8th graf, ``Jaffna once...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil militants today attacked Sri
Lankan troopers escorting Sinhalese laborers in a northeastern
jungle and killed at least 21 soldiers, military officials said.
   Also today, Sinhalese radicals detonated a remote-controlled
bomb under a Sri Lankan army truck, killing one soldier and
injuring three, a military official said. He blamed the attack near
Angunakolapelessa, 80 miles southeast of Colombo, on the People's
Liberation Front, a nationalist Sinhalese group.
   The attack in the northeastern jungle was the third blamed on
Tamil militants since Thursday. Authorities say at least 79 people
have died since Thursday despite a government cease-fire called in
an attempt to persuade Tamil rebels and Sinhalese militants to
surrender.
   At least four laborers were wounded in the jungle attack near
the village of Parakramapura in Weli Oya district, said officials,
who cannot be identified under briefing rules. At least 21 soldiers
were killed, they said.
   The village is about 150 miles northeast of Colombo.
   At least 45 people, many of them Sinhalese, died when a car bomb
exploded in the port city of Trincomalee on Thursday.
   On Friday, another car bomb exploded in the Tamil-dominated town
of Jaffna, 185 miles north of Colombo, leaving 12 people dead and
18 critically injured. Most of those killed and injured were Tamil
students, a military official said.
   ``We believe the bomb went off prematurely when passing the
university and was meant for Indian troops manning a small camp 75
yards away from the university,'' said one of the military
officials in Colombo.
   A leader of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest
Tamil guerrilla group that has been fighting the Sri Lankan
government and Indian peacekeeping troops, also said 12 people were
killed, mostly Tamil students.
   The Tiger leader, who spoke on condition of anonymity in
Colombo, said he did not know who was responsible for the bomb.
   Jaffna once was the chief stronghold of the Tigers, but the
separatist guerrillas' open presence in the town was halted by the
Indian force that was dispatched to Sri Lanka in July 1987 in an
effort to disarm the Tigers and enforce a India-Sri Lanka peace
pact.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa's government on Wednesday
announced a one-week cease-fire in an effort to halt the bloodshed.
The president offered to talk with both Tamil and Sinhalese
radicals ``any time, any place.''
   The Tamil Tigers rejected the cease-fire. The People's
Liberation Front, in a statement to local newspapers, questioned
the government's sincerity.
   Tamil separatists launched their battle in 1983, attacking the
Sinhalese-dominated government's troops and Sinhalese civilians.
The Tigers rejected government efforts to pacify the Tamil
militants by offering them a measure of autonomy.
   The Sinhalese extremists began a campaign of assassinations,
saying the government offered too many concessions to the Tamil
minority.
   Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, comprise 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, account
for 18 percent.
   More than 12,500 people, including at least 800 Indian soldiers,
have died in six years of warfare.
</TEXT>
