<DOCNO> AP890415-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-YellowstoneWildlife     04-15 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone Wildlife,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Wildlife Find New Vegetation Amid Charred Landscape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elk, bison and other
wildlife that survived a rough winter and a slaughter by hunters
are beginning to benefit from the fires that ravaged the world's
oldest national park last summer.
   As the snow melts over Yellowstone National Park's 2.2 million
acres, new vegetation is springing from soil enriched by nutrients
that were released by the burning.
   In addition, moose, antelope, mule deer, bears and other animals
will enjoy new summer grazing areas burned into previously dense
stands of lodgepole pine.
   ``The majority of the fire effects will be positive,'' said a
report last month by the Greater Yellowstone Coordinating
Committee, ``including increased production of grasses, forbs and
shrubs; higher protein content in forages; lower fiber content;
earlier spring green-up, and more diverse diets for elk.''
   Politicians have argued that the National Park Service and U.S.
Forest Service mismanaged the forest fires, which blackened nearly
half the park.
   But not all the emerging scenes in Yellowstone are picturesque.
Many hillsides and meadows are littered with the carcasses of elk
and bison that failed to survive the winter. By historical
standards the season was not harsh, but it was severe enough to
kill off many old animals that had survived the unusually mild
winters of the past decade.
   And when many elk and bison looking for forage trudged north
beyond the park's boundaries, hunters flocked into Gardiner, Mont.,
to shoot them. Montana officials worried the bison would infect
cattle with brucellosis, which causes cows to abort.
   By the end of this past winter's hunting seasons, Yellowstone
officials estimated 2,400 elk were taken along with 527 bison.
   The animals' deaths generated debate on the need for more winter
range for the animals north of Yellowstone and on the lack of
environmental logic used when the park was carved out of Wyoming,
Idaho and Montana 117 years ago.
   ``Park boundaries are drawn politically,'' said Stu Coleman,
Yellowstone's resource management specialist. ``That's why they're
so nice and straight. If in 1872 they had thought ecologically,
they probably would have stepped back, studied the situation and
drawn the boundaries ecologically.''
   Earlier this month the Greater Yellowstone Coordinating
Committee set a goal of raising $6.7 million to acquire 18,000
acres of private land north of the park.
   ``We don't bill it as, `This is the only solution,''' said
Yellowstone Superintendent Bob Barbee. But ``it would relieve the
problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890415-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial Bjt   04-15 1049</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, Bjt,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Practiced Observers Analyze North Testimony, Trial Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North may have severely hurt his
credibility by telling jurors at his Iran-Contra trial he bought an
$8,000 used car with cash kept at home in a closet, legal experts
say.
   ``The most damaging thing that happened to him during the trial
was the cross-examination on the money. That was just
devastating,'' said Washington attorney John Nields, who was one of
North's interrogators at the 1987 congressional hearings when he
was chief counsel to the House Iran-Contra committee.
   Nields and three other lawyers interviewed after eight weeks of
trial testimony ended Friday said the cross-examination of North by
prosecutor John Keker may be damaging for the defense.
   Final arguments are to begin Tuesday and the case could go to
the jury by Thursday.
   One of the lawyers interviewed said the former National Security
Council aide might well be acquitted of the most serious charges,
including an allegation he pocketed money from Nicaraguan rebels.
   But all four agreed that North's assertion that he covered the
1985 car purchase from a $15,000 stash of money in a box bolted to
the closet floor was troublesome for the defense.
   ``To have come up with a locked box on the floor for your
explanation for large expenses when you are taking travelers checks
from your Contra kitty looks terrible,'' Nields said.
   ``It is fishy to have $15,000 in your closet, nobody does
that,'' said Paul Rothstein, a professor at Georgetown University
Law Center. ``I am not entirely convinced the jury is going to
think its smelly, it just depends on their personal experience.''
   Besides charges he lied about his secret help of the Nicaraguan
rebels, North is also accused of diverting to his personal use some
$4,300 of the $90,000 to $100,000 worth of travelers checks given
to him by a Contra leader.
   The retired Marine lieutenant colonel testified that he only
reimbursed himself for expenses incurred helping the rebels.
   He told jurors that on the advice of the late CIA Director
William Casey he destroyed ledger he kept to document all
disbursements from the secret operational fund.
   North also denied Keker's suggestion that he took $3,000 in cash
from arms dealer Richard V. Secord _ to help buy an $8,038 used car
in 1985.
   North said the money came from a ``family fund'' he kept in a
metal box bolted to the floor of his closet. The money was amassed
from an insurance settlement and change he emptied from his pants
pockets every Friday night, North said.
   North said he took $5,000 to buy a station wagon but decided
instead to purchase the more expensive car. North testified he put
down the $5,000 and paid the additional $3,000 later for the GMC
Suburban vehicle.
   But a used-car salesman disputed this testimony on Friday,
saying North had called him several times inquiring about a
newspaper ad for the GMC vehicle. North told him he intended to
partially finance the purchase through the White House Credit
Union, the salesman said.
   A former National Security Council secretary who disbursed
expense accounts, said North was so pinched for cash in 1984 he
complained he couldn't buy lunch or gas to drive home.
   She said these complaints stopped in 1985, when North controlled
a secret fund for the Contras in his office safe.
   ``I think the business of the purchase of the car and perhaps
the rebuttal testimony from the used-car salesman and the secretary
from the National Security Council may be damaging,'' said former
Watergate prosecutor Richard Ben-Veniste.
   ``About the time these payments start coming in, the jury may
conclude that the temptation for all of this money was just too
much for Ollie North,'' said Ben-Veniste.
   ``If the jury finds he was involved in self-dealing then his
whole posture of moral rectitude is not going to wash,'' said
Ben-Veniste, who stressed that he did not attend the trial based
his views solely only on reports about the proceeding.
   Alan M. Dershowitz, a Harvard University law professor, said the
defense failure to question North again after Keker's damaging
cross-examination was a ``serious mistake.''
   Jurors were left with an image of North explaining how he used a
department-store typewriter to type letters to help fabricate proof
he paid for a $13,800 security fence around his home.
   North said he accepted the fence to protect his family in the
face of terrorist threats but admitted the cover-up.
   ``The last image they (jurors) had of North is being destroyed
on going and typing those letters,'' Dershowitz said.
   North is also charged with illegally accepting the security
system from Secord.
   Dershowitz also faulted defense attorney Brendan V. Sullivan Jr.
for not bringing out the car-purchase story during North's direct
testimony instead of leaving it to be developed by Keker on
cross-examination.
   ``Sullivan left far too much for Keker. He didn't sufficiently
deflect and defuse the nuclear weapons that Keker had in his
arsenal,'' Dershowitz said.
   The car story should have been told ``to the point of boredom so
that when Keker crossed on it the jury would have been yawning.''
   ``Unless North didn't tell his lawyers, I think Sullivan just
bungled it,'' Dershowitz said.
   Sullivan has refused to comment outside the courtroom on any
aspect of the case against North.
   Rothstein, alone, said North made a strong case for acquittal,
saying his explanation about the travelers check _ except the
car-purchase account _ was ``a believable story.''
   All agreed that the equivocal testimony by former national
security adviser Robert McFarlane weakened the prosecution's case
that North lied to Congress.
   McFarlane blamed North for giving him false information for
letters that the former national security adviser wrote to
Congress. But he backed off major points and changed his story.
   Although McFarlane testified as a prosecution witness, ``he blew
hot and cold,'' Rothstein said.
   Rothstein suggested that Sullivan may be gently suggesting that
the jury convict North of the security-fence charge but not the
other charges.
   ``That's a nice compromise verdict that the jury can find if
they are torn between guilt or innocence. That's not too bad a
result for North,'' Rothstein said.
   The gratuity charge carries a 2-year sentence, the lightest
penalty of the 12 counts against North.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
