<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-StadiumCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0464 04-15 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stadium Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barrier Collapses At Soccer Match; Scores Reported Injured, Possibly
Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with witness saying some people died,
no reports of violence before collapse, details from scene. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stadium barrier collapsed Saturday
from the weight of thousands of fans at a soccer match, injuring
scores of people. One witness said some fans were killed.
   Police did not immediately confirm any deaths, but many people
lay on the field being treated by emergency ambulance crews. Dozens
were carried away on stretchers or on advertising billboards.
   British Broadcasting Corp. radio and television said the
incident at Hillsborough stadium in northern England was
``extremely serious.''
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said some of
the victims were given cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
   The accident occurred at the English Football Association Cup
semifinal match between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest. The game
was officially called off about an hour after the incident.
   The game in Sheffield had been going on only six minutes when a
barrier holding thousands of Liverpool fans behind one of the goals
collapsed, crushing scores of spectators and forcing others onto
the field.
   Reports said many of the Liverpool fans had entered the section
without tickets through a broken gate.
   ``People just walked in that gate and the police just let them
walk in. There are people lying dead there on the floor,'' one
unidentified fan told the BBC.
   Officially, the game attracted a capacity crowd at the
54,000-seat Hillsborough facility. Broadcast reports, however, said
hundreds more attended.
   Police confirmed there was ``a surge of fans'' at the Liverpool
supporters' end of the stadium. Reports said violence did not play
any part in the crush, which appeared to be purely a result of
overcrowding.
   Saturday's accident came less than a week after the ruling body
of European soccer, the Union of European Football Associations,
announced it was lifting its ban on English teams in time for the
1990-91 season.
   The ban was imposed after the May, 1985 Heysel stadium tragedy
in Brussels, Belgium when 39 supporters, most of them Italian, died
in a stampede by Liverpool fans at the European Champions Cup final
against Juventus of Turin.
   The English Football Association Cup is the world's oldest
domestic single elimination soccer tournament and the winners of
the Liverpool-Forest semifinal were assured a place in next month's
championship game at Wembley Stadium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
