<DOCNO> AP890415-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LibrarianPriest Bjt   04-15 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Librarian Priest, Bjt,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Welcome Back, Father: Priest's Selection Breaks Library Silence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The appointment of a Jesuit as president of the
New York Public Library has pitted some of the city's literary
lions against each other and raised questions about whether his vow
of papal obedience could compromise scholarship, free speech and
the rights of homosexuals.
   The Rev. Timothy Healy, president of Georgetown University,
agreed in February to succeed Vartan Gregorian, who was leaving to
become president of Brown University.
   At Georgetown, Healy had a reputation as a good teacher and an
exceptional fund-raiser _ the school's endowment rose from $30
million to almost $250 million during his 13 years there. Not
coincidentally, the library, which bills itself as one of the five
greatest in the world with four research branches and 81
neighborhood branches, is in the midst of a campaign to raise $157
million from private sources.
   The selection was greeted by a wave of hosannas. The president
of the American Council on Education said Healy would ``get the
movers and shakers of New York interested in the library.'' Former
U.N. Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick, who teaches at Georgetown,
called Healy ``a nearly perfect fit'' for the job and a man who
``really loves New York'' and has ``the style of a Richard Burton.''
   The 65-year-old Healy, a native New Yorker who once worked
summers stacking books at the library, seemed to have found a
fitting place to end his career. ``It's home,'' he said. ``I grew
up in this town.''
   But last month the weekly Village Voice ran a story headlined
``Scholar or Bigot?'' that focused on Healy's clashes with gay
student groups at Georgetown, and a New York Times editorialist
wondered why a church with a critical shortage of priests could
find no better use for this one than running a public library.
   In a letter to the Times, author Gay Talese wondered about a
conflict between the Jesuit's vow of obedience to the pope and the
librarian's obligations to ``those who disagree with his church.''
   Talese's letter brought a rebuttal from author Garry Wills, who
accused him of ``raising the issue of `Catholic loyalty' that was
brought against John F. Kennedy in 1960. ... Is Mr. Talese hinting
that an American Catholic cannot believe in freedom of the press?''
   Next up was ``Catch-22'' author Joseph Heller, who said Wills
missed the point. Healy, he wrote, is not just any Catholic, he is
a priest of a church with ``stern, outspoken attitudes toward such
matters as obscenity, heresy, blasphemy, birth control and a host
of others.'' The letter wondered if a priest could be head ``of a
secular, public institution.''
   Meanwhile, some homosexuals complained that Healy refused to
recognize gay student groups at Georgetown and tried to deny them
access to school facilities. They also questioned how he would
treat homosexuals who work at the library. Other library staffers
said his presence could have a chilling effect on their efforts to
foster knowledge on such subjects as AIDS.
   Healy declined a request for an interview, but in an interview
with the Times he said there would be no conflict between his
religious and academic vocations.
   ``I work for the board of trustees,'' he said. ``No
ecclesiastical authority has any power over me in the conduct of my
business at the library. None.'' If a conflict arose, he said, he
would quit the job.
   In recent years, several priests and nuns have run into
conflicts because of their secular jobs in government.
   The Rev. Robert Drinan of Boston, a Jesuit, gave up his seat in
the U.S. House in 1980 when the pope decreed that a priest could
not also hold political office.
   A nun, Arlene Violet, quit the Sisters of Mercy to become Rhode
Island attorney general in 1984. Another nun, Agnes Mary Monsour,
chose to leave the sisterhood to remain director of Michigan social
services, which handles some abortion funding.
   But Healy said that while he served as vice chancellor for
academic affairs at the City University of New York, a public
institution, from 1969 to 1976, ``there was never any religious
tension.'' He also noted that he has permission from his order to
run a public library.
   About the sanctity of research, Healy said that at Georgetown,
he was acting as the head of a Catholic institution that could not
condone sex outside marriage. ``The New York Public Library is not
a Catholic institution,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
