<DOCNO> AP890415-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Racketeering     04-15 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Racketeering,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Drop Eastern Suit Against Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Saturday said he has refused to dismiss a
$1.5 billion racketeering lawsuit accusing Eastern's unions of
trying to wreck the airline in order to force its sale at a loss.
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler said he was not ruling on
the merits of Eastern's arguments, only the legal requirements for
pursuing the lawsuit.
   The suit was filed last May, before the 6-week-old strike by the
Machinists union forced the airline to seek bankruptcy protection.
   A $464 million deal by former baseball commissioner Peter
Ueberroth to buy strike-crippled Eastern fell through last week
over union demands that a trustee replace Texas Air Corp. chairman
Frank Lorenzo while the airline changes hands.
   Eastern's suit seeks to hold the Machinists, the Air Line Pilots
Association and several union officials responsible for any damages
from a forced sale.
   It accuses ALPA and the Machinists of ``attempting to obtain
ownership and control of Eastern through extortion to destroy the
company's business and smear its reputation,'' said Eastern
spokesman Robin Matell.
   The judge said he will issue a written ruling this week.
</TEXT>
