<FIRST>r w AM-Soviets-Terrorism     04-15 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviets-Terrorism,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antiterrorist Measures to Be Discussed by Baker and Soviet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will
discuss possible U.S.-Soviet cooperation in fighting terrorism when
he meets with his Soviet counterpart in Moscow next month,
administration officials say.
   The issue arose briefly when Baker met with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze in Vienna in March, and since then
U.S. officials have been exploring ways they think the Soviets
might be able to help, the sources said.
   The U.S. view of such cooperation soured a bit following
disclosure recently that Moscow secretly sold Su-24 bombers to
Libya.
   Libya leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi supports terrorism, Baker said
in a speech Friday. ``And how does this sale assist in the
worldwide efforts _ supposedly supported by Moscow _ to control
chemical weapons that Libya is developing at its Rabta plant?''
   The State Department counterrorism office remains cool to the
idea of cooperating with the Kremlin, but it has found some support
with the European bureau, which handles day-to-day affairs with
Moscow, said administration officials who spoke on condition they
not be identified by name.
   Baker, in confirmation hearings before the Senate, said he
wanted to discuss terrorism within the framework of ongoing
U.S.-Soviet negotiations.
   A U.S. position is being prepared for the Baker-Shevardnadze
meeting to determine the extent to which the Soviets are willing to
cooperate, the sources said.
   The department's annual report on terrorism said that despite a
``more constructive approach ... the Soviets continued to provide
arms, training, and materiel and diplomatic support to a range of
states and groups linked to terrorism.''
   Hope may be drawn from the fact that ``the Soviets are training
fewer people overall,'' said an administration terrorism expert.
   Moscow and its allies, according to Western analysts and
intelligence operatives, have trained Palestinian and other
terrorists and provided safe haven for such terrorists as Abu
Nidal, who for years was allowed to maintain an office in Poland.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has said he was prepared
to cooperate with the United States in fighting terrorism. A senior
official of the KGB intelligence service said in a Radio Moscow
interview in January that in counterrorism, ``we are willing, if
there is a need, to cooperate even with the CIA, British
intelligence, and the Israeli Mossad and other services in the
West.''
   In one concrete example, last December Soviet authorities
negotiated directly with Israel _ with which they do not have
diplomatic ties _ and obtained the return of four people who
commandeered a Soviet plane to Israel.
   State Department officials also were heartened by an unusual
U.S.-Soviet conference last January in Moscow, which did not
involve government-to-government contacts but was attended by
several leading American experts on terrorism.
   Two of the Americans, Robert Kupperman of the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington, and Brian
Jenkins of the Rand Corp., sometimes work as government
consultants, although both stressed that they went to Moscow as
private citizens.
   The Russian side included officials from the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and the Ministry of Internal Affairs, which runs the
domestic police.
   Kupperman said he was surprised at how far the Soviets were
willing to go in exploring specific steps each nation could take
against actions that, for example, ``could involve mass casualties,
including nuclear, chemical or biological incidents.''
   Jenkins, who is publishing a report on the meeting, said the
participants ``backed away from some of the most contentious
issues, such as training the Soviet Union has in the past supplied
to some of these organizations.''
   Jenkins, describing himself as ``hardnosed skeptic,'' proposed
establishing guidelines to judge whether the Soviets are in fact
cooperating.
   Such guidelines would provide a rough measure of Soviet
political support for so-called ``national liberation movements,''
military aid to guerrillas, and help the Soviets give to terrorists
such as Abu Nidal.
   But, said Jenkins, ``we cannot establish impossible criteria. We
have to acknowledge that the Soviet government is big, with
competing elements, and some of those elements are going to
continue to do things that we think they ought not to do.''
   ``We cannot find out whether this is a ploy without exploring
this further,'' said Jenkins.
   ``We also have to keep in mind that we have difficulties
sustaining international cooperation against terrorism even among
countries with whom we have shared common political and legal
traditions for two centuries and who have been our military allies
for four decades,'' said Jenkins.
</TEXT>
