<FIRST>u a PM-LottoFever 1stLd-Writethru a0412 04-15 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lotto Fever, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0412,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ticket Sales Soar As Biggest U.S. Lottery Game Draws Near</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with jackpot raised to $65 million,
rate at 15,000 a minute. PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Players said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Would-be millionaires today bought 15,000 tickets
a minute for a shot at $65 million, the biggest lottery jackpot in
U.S. history.
   ``I don't know anyone who hasn't bought one and it seems like
everyone is talking about it this time around,'' said Chicago
flight attendant Jane Chartier. ``There really is a fever about
it.''
   By Friday night more than 31.7 million tickets had been sold for
today's 6:57 p.m. drawing, said Illinois lottery spokeswoman Kathy
Rem.
   She said about a million tickets were sold hourly during most of
the day, with people lining up at lottery outlets. By 6 p.m., sales
registered at more than 1.6 million an hour, or 465 a second, she
said.
   Tickets were reported selling at a rate of 250 a second today.
   Players said they were planning to watch the televised drawing
and hope for the best.
   Some said their hopes were boosted by good omens.
   Ted Tyson of Napa, Calif., in Chicago for an International
Business Machines Corp. training program, said he ate at a Chinese
restaurant, cracked open a fortune cookie, and read: ``The star of
riches is shining upon you.''
   Mary Hickey of Chicago said she ``just had a good feeling _ you
know, like you do sometimes when you're playing poker.''
   Even Larry Eyestone of Urbana, who won a $1.4 million Illinois
Lotto jackpot in 1983, said he had hope of scoring another win.
   ``I figure lightning can strike again,'' he said.
   In the drawing, six numbers between 1 and 54 are chosen, and the
winner must match all six.
   There are 25.8 million possible combinations of numbers that
could be drawn, Ms. Rem said.
   Gambling travelers lined up at O'Hare International Airport,
where sales for today's drawing have been just about double the
average, said Bob Flynn of the Paralyzed Veterans of America, which
runs the airport's six Lotto kiosks.
   The jackpot for Saturday Lotto drawings begin at a base of $5
million. But the last winner was March 18, and unclaimed prizes and
excess ticket sale proceeds are rolled over into subsequent prizes.
   Ms. Rem said a state tax would claim 2.5 percent of the prize,
and the federal tax would be 20 percent. This jackpot guarantees a
single winner 20 annual payments of $3.1 million. Multiple winners
would split the winnings.
   Lottery officials say people have called from Italy, France,
England and the Netherlands to ask how they can play.
   And of course, across Illinois, people were contemplating a win.
   ``My ex-wife would marry me back, believe me,'' said Jim Ocello
of Chicago.
   ``If I won, no one would find me again,'' said John Roate of
Springfield. ``I'd move to some place warm. With that kind of
money, you could probably buy an island.''
</TEXT>
