<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0425 04-15 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0425,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Cleanup Plan Due as Oil Spill Reaches Second National Park</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead; SUBS 6th graf pvs, `The weather ...' to UPDATE
with wind changing direction; INSERTS two graf after 8th graf pvs, `Oil
has ...' with pilot's account.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VDX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's worst-ever oil spill reached the
shore of a second national park, raising fears today that bears
would join sea mammals, birds and deer as casualties of the Exxon
Valdez wreck.
   Oil washed up Friday at the Big River area along the northern
coast of Katmai National Park, an undeveloped area beside the
Shelikof Strait, more than 250 miles from where the tanker rammed a
reef on March 24.
   Observers from a plane saw a bear dig clams from the oil-tainted
sand, said Park Service spokesman John Quinley.
   ``We've seen pictures of dead deer in Prince William Sound that
ate oil-tainted kelp, and it looks like we could be seeing brown
bear meeting the same fate,'' Quinley said.
   Park officials said bears are just beginning to come out of
hibernation and heading to beaches to feed.
   The weather forecast held more bad news: winds from the
southeast were expected to push more oil ashore in the area.
   Exxon was to hand over a detailed shoreline cleanup plan today
to the head of the Coast Guard, Adm. Paul Yost. The plan was to
include the number of people and the amount of gear needed to begin
scouring some of the 3,000 beaches blackened by the oil spill.
   Oil has been washing ashore at Kenai Fjords National Park for a
week, and residents of such fishing and tourist towns as Homer,
Kodiak, Seldovia and Port Graham were preparing to try to block the
spreading spill today.
   But encouraging signs also emerged.
   Pilot Bill DeCreeft flew over the Nuka Bay area late Friday to
help track the oil's progress. ``I was quite encouraged,'' he said
today. ``I saw places where oil had hit the beach, but essentially
it looks like it always did.''
   Big River was No. 2 on a list of nine places at Katmai where
park officials believe floating booms may be able to shield salmon
spawning areas, brown bear habitat, bird nesting areas and native
Alaskan sites from the ribbons of oil.
   Exxon was to send ships with booms in today, but some residents
of Kodiak, the nation's No. 1 port in terms of dollars earned, were
unwilling to wait that long, Quinley said Friday night.
   ``Twelve fishing vessels set out for the Katmai coast tonight to
try to control the oil,'' he said.
   He had no details on how much oil had washed up, and Exxon's
offices had closed for the night.
   By Friday, the thick oil and sheen from the crash of the Exxon
Valdez tanker had drifted down Prince William Sound, defiling
thousands of boulder-strewn beaches, 225 miles southwest to the tip
of the Kenai Peninsula, where sea currents divide.
   Some oil then moved down the east side of the Kodiak Islands,
with spottings reported at Afognak Island and as far south as the
waters of the community of Kodiak, about 300 miles from the
accident site.
   The oil that was on the other side of the Kodiak archipelago and
had threatened the Katmai park included a 40-square-mile patch of
heavy oil and sheen in Shelikof Strait.
   Thousands of birds and mammals have died in the washed-up muck,
and there were continued fears of damage to salmon, herring, crab
and other rich fisheries throughout the region.
   The Exxon Valdez, a 987-foot tanker, veered sharply out of
shipping lanes and rammed the reef early Good Friday morning.
   Yost, the Coast Guard chief who has taken over direction of the
cleanup, has called the effort to deal with the spill a ``war.''
   He vowed to put soldiers on the beaches for the cleanup, if
needed, but said he would promise no miracles in what is sure to be
a monthslong effort. He and state authorities have been highly
critical of Exxon's cleanup efforts during the past three weeks.
   Scientists were assembling a list of critical and non-critical
beaches for cleanup. Yost said high-pressure, hot-water jets would
be used to cleanse at least some of the shore, although the method
likely would leave behind sterile ``dead beaches.''
   ``It's my view that we'd do better with high pressure and heat
and doing some environmental damage,'' he said. ``The beaches will
recolonize in a year or two. They won't if the oil is not removed.''
</TEXT>
