<DOCNO> AP890415-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-HospitalofDeath Bjt   04-15 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital of Death, Bjt,0940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austrians Grapple with Case of `Incomprehensible' Killings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The magnolia tree is in full bloom and
sprinklers cast a soft mist on the flower beds. Lainz hospital's
well-tended grounds are peaceful, a quiet facade behind which a
tale of multiple murder was played out.
   The shadow of death lies over Pavilion Five, where four nurses'
aides have confessed to killing at least 49 elderly patients with
injections, which they are not supposed to administer, or by
forcing water into a victim's lungs.
   They claimed to have done it out of mercy, but police say the
methods were not merciful.
   Tragedy, grief and misfortune are ever-present in hospitals, and
people who work in them know the analgesic value of routine.
   In the wards and corridors of Lainz, it continues unchanged.
Beds are made, patients fed, temperatures taken.
   So strong was the impulse to cling to routine despite the
killings that, when a reporter asked to interview a ranking
hospital doctor, a secretary asked: ``What's it about?''
   An hour later, she too was struck by the sense of shock and
depression patients say has begun to stalk the wards, and said with
a gasp: ``The boss has been suspended!''
   That was five days after Austria first learned of the killings
in the hospital department run by the suspended doctor, Franz
Pesendorfer, a respected internist in his early 50s.
   At first, the story seemed too incredible even for tabloids that
deal in lurid tales of sex and crime. The Neue Kronen Zeitung,
Austria's largest- circulation daily, carried a bold headline but
had only a small story inside.
   Two days later, when four nursing assistants were said to have
confessed to at least 44 killings, the story covered seven pages in
the paper's editions for Sunday, April 9.
   Leaks to news media, apparently from police, revealed such
graphic details that police chief Guenter Boegl reluctantly
confirmed the stories at an unusual Sunday news conference.
   The medical profession was stunned.
   ``I wasn't surprised; I wasn't horrified. I just couldn't
imagine how it happened,'' said Hildegard Fach, head of the
national union for nurses and their aides.
   ``It's incomprehensible,'' she added in an interview six days
after the first word of the murders. ``Everywhere I go, colleagues
are saying, `Can you imagine?'''
   As the shock sank in, public anger mounted and trust in Vienna's
overtaxed health services began to evaporate.
   By Friday, a week after the first reports, city health director
Alois Stacher had received so many reports of nurses and their
aides being yelled at in the streets that he appealed to Viennese
to stop.
   Psychiatrist Stefan Rudas said of the sense of mistrust in
hospitals: ``It's as if waiters in a restaurant had served poison
or teachers killed their pupils.''
   Ms. Fach said she hopes one result of the killings will be more
money for health services.
   ``People in Austria ... will have to realize that health costs
money and that you can't scrimp,'' she said.
   Medical students in Vienna often say there is little prospect of
finding jobs in city hospitals, although they know they are needed.
   According to Ms. Fach, the city needs 200-400 qualified nurses.
She said a study last year found that 1,600 more were necessary if
patients were to be guaranteed ``optimal care'' and nurses a
43-hour work week.
   She and other medical personnel have said repeatedly that Vienna
hospitals only keep going by violating regulations that bar nurses'
aides from giving injections. Except in emergencies, doctors are
not even supposed to turn injections over to registered nurses.
   Waltraud Wagner, the 30-year-old nursing aid said to be
responsible for most of the Lainz killings, was reported to have
``put to rest'' elderly patients with injections of insulin,
tranquilizers and other medicines.
   According to the police warrant, she showed fellow aides Maria
Gruber, 25; Irene Leidolf, 27, and Stefanie Mayer, 50, how to
prepare the deadly injections, and let them watch while she held a
patient's tongue and poured water into the lungs.
   Two central questions still unanswered are: Why did they do it
and how did the killings continue over several years without
exposure?
   All the women except Ms. Mayer are from large families in small
villages. Their pay is low and they had little spare money, but
they got no richer by killing impoverished old people.
   A twisted sense of mercy killing or a sense of power may have
played a part, but that would not explain why they worked together,
as Ms. Fach noted.
   Nearly all medical personnel in other countries have acted alone
when they killed elderly patients and claimed they wanted to
release them from agony.
   Police warrants suggest the killings began in 1983.
Investigators were called to Lainz hospital almost exactly a year
ago after Dr. Pesendorfer heard rumors that nurses aides in his
department were killing patients.
   He and another doctor refused, in an action now widely
criticized, to name the doctor who had passed on the initial tip
from a nurses' aide.
   Investigator Max Edelbacher said police finally tracked down the
doctor, Alois Waschnig, and played ``almost a game of
hide-and-seek'' to speak with him.
   Waschnig refused to reveal his source and Edelbacher said police
could not force him to do so.
   An autopsy at the time on an 84-year-old woman Ms. Wagner is
said to have admitted killing also turned up nothing suspicious and
the case was closed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
