<DOCNO> AP890415-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1411EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-StadiumCollapse 6thLd-Writethru a0501 04-15 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stadium Collapse, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0501,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fence Collapses At British Soccer Match, 95 People Killed, 180 Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON4,5,6</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE death toll, raise reference to those without
tickets. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chain-link fence holding back
thousands of people at a soccer match collapsed today, and a
spokesman for an ambulance company said 95 people were crushed to
death and 180 injured.
   Some of the fans apparently died when the surging crowd jammed
them against the fence, located at one end of the stadium. Others
were killed when the barrier caved in and the crowd fell toward the
field. The fence was topped with curved steel bars designed to stop
spectators from climbing over it.
   News reports indicated the area of the stadium was overcrowded
because many fans had entered without tickets.
   Television pictures showed scores of fans lying on the field
being treated by emergency ambulance crews. Dozens of fans were
carried away on stretchers or on advertising billboards used as
makeshift beds.
   The accident occurred in the opening minutes of the English
Football Association Cup semifinal between Liverpool and Nottingham
Forest, two leading teams, at Hillsborough stadium in Sheffield,
150 miles north of London.
   The game was six minutes old when a fence holding thousands of
Liverpool fans behind one of the goals collapsed, crushing the
spectators.
   Ray Clarke, spokesman for the Ambulance Service, said in a
telephone interview that 95 people died and 180 were injured in the
accident, the worst disaster ever at a British soccer event.
(Although Americans call the game soccer, all other countries refer
to it as football.)
   Football Association officials said many of the Liverpool
backers entered the section without tickets through a gate that was
either broken or opened, swelling the section allocated for its
fans beyond the permitted capacity.
   ``It looks a desperate situation,'' said the Football
Association's chief executive, Graham Kelly. ``I am deeply sorry
that the day has ended this way. We had six minutes of football and
one and a half hours of absolute bedlam.''
   Officially, the game attracted a capacity crowd at the
54,000-seat Hillsborough facility.
   But reports said hundreds more Liverpool fans without tickets
poured through a turnstile gate behind one of the goals, packing an
area marked off for the team's followers and crushing those at the
front of the stand.
   ``A gate or gates were opened or broken and fans came in,''
Kelly said. ``There were too many fans in the area, obviously, and
they spilled over. There will be a full investigation.''
   One unidentified fan told the BBC: ``People just walked in that
gate and the police just let them walk in. There are people lying
dead there on the floor. It was chockablock and as people tried to
get into the front the police tried to force them back into the
ground. This ground was allocated for an F.A. Cup Final because it
could have dealt with any problems and now it hasn't.''
   The English Football Association Cup is the world's oldest,
domestic single elimination soccer tournament and the winners of
the Liverpool-Forest semifinal were assured a place in next month's
championship game at Wembley stadium.
   Ninety minutes after the incident, the ground was virtually
cleared by police and the game canceled.
   Reports said crowd violence played no part in the crush, which
appeared to be purely a result of overcrowding.
   The tragedy came less than a week after the ruling body of
European soccer, the Union of European Football Associaitons,
announced it was lifting its ban on English teams in time for the
1990-91 season.
   The ban was imposed after the May 1985 Heysel stadium tragedy in
Brussels, Belgium, in which 39 supporters, most of them Italian,
died in a stampede by Liverpool fans at the European Champions Cup
final against Juventus of Turin.
   Today's disaster was the worst ever at a British soccer event.
   On Jan. 2, 1971, 66 people died when an overcrowded stairway
collapsed during a local soccer match between Glasgow Rangers and
Celtic in Glasgow, Scotland. Fifty-six fans died on May 11, 1985,
when a fire engulfed the main stand during a match at Bradford
City's soccer stadium near Sheffield.
   The worst soccer disaster on record took place on May 24, 1964,
when rioting left nearly 300 dead and 500 injured after Argentina
beat Peru on a last-minute goal in Lima.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
