<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0505 04-15 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0505,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator Killed in Shelling, French Aid Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs with to UPDATE with two more people killed;
Pickup 5th graf, ``An Italian ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 72-year-old Christian parliamentarian
died Saturday when a rocket hit his apartment building during
shelling duels between Syrian and Christian gunners, police said.
   A Lebanese navy gunboat ferried 14 badly wounded Christians to a
French naval vessel anchored off Beirut as a French humanitarian
aid mission got under way. It was unclear whether Moslems would
participate.
   Police said intermittent shelling duels intensified before
sundown as gunners from both sides blasted Beirut and its
surroundings, killing four people and wounding 31.
   The casualties raised the overall toll to 219 dead and 758
wounded from the five-week battle between Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000
mostly Christian troops and an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces.
   An Italian tanker with a cargo of diesel oil, the Cochinella,
was hit by a shell eight miles off Beirut on Saturday, an Italian
Embassy official said.
   The embassy's charge d'affaires, Attilo Iannucci, said the top
deck was damaged but none of the 14 Italian crewmen was hurt. He
said the ship, which was heading for the Christian port of Jounieh
north of Beirut, was returning to Cyprus.
   A police spokesman said the legislator, Louis Abu Sharaf, was
killed when a rocket landed near his apartment on the third floor
of an eight-story building in Christian east Beirut. He said the
rockets were launched from the divided capital's Moslem sector.
   Abu Sharaf was the first legislator to die in a shelling attack
in Lebanon's 15-year-old civil war. He represented Christian
Kesrouan province since 1960.
   His death raised to 23 the number of deputies who died since the
last parliamentary elections in 1972.
   The war between Christians and Moslems has prevented
parliamentary elections since then, and Abu Sharif's death reduced
the number of deputies in the 99-seat house to 75.
   The current violence erupted March 8 after Aoun ordered a
blockade of militia-run ports that strip the state treasury of
about $1 million annually in lost customs dues.
   Druse militiamen started shelling the Christian enclave in
retaliation.
   The Syrians, who maintain 40,000 troops in predominantly Moslem
areas under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate, joined in the
shelling duel on the side of the Druse.
   The French naval ship La Rance dropped anchor 10 miles off the
Christian port of Jounieh, where France's minister for humanitarian
aid, Bernard Kouchner, was supervising a mercy mission.
   France has strong ties with Lebanon, which it ruled from World
War I until independence in 1943.
   The fully equipped hospital ship was one of two carrying
humanitarian aid, which French officials say is intended for both
Christians and Moslems.
   But Moslems have said France was taking sides in the war and
renounced claims to their part of the aid.
   According to an agreement Kouchner reached with Moslems, the
second ship was to unload its cargo of fuel oil at two government
ports in Moslem and Christian sectors. The fuel is badly needed to
keep Lebanon's power stations operating.
   A Lebanese navy gunboat took wounded Christians to the La Rance
and then returned with medicine for hospitals in the
310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of Beirut.
   A Moslem official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Kouchner was trying to persuade Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem
Cabinet in Lebanon's dual government, to allow a similar evacuation
of wounded Moslems from west Beirut.
   The rival Christian and Moslem Cabinets emerged in September
after outgoing President Amin Gemayel named Aoun, a Maronite
Catholic like himself, to head an interim military Cabinet pending
Parliament's election of a new head of state.
   But Moslems and leftists pledged allegiance to Hoss, who
governed under Gemayel. They claimed Aoun's appointment violated an
unwritten convention that made Lebanon's president a Maronite, the
premier a Sunni and the Parliament Speaker a Shiite Moslem.
</TEXT>
