<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Church     04-15 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Church,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishop Says Church Is Under Attack by Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAHAYAG, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic bishop told
mourners at the funeral of a slain priest Saturday that the
military is persecuting the church and President Corazon Aquino is
ignoring its abuses.
   The Rev. Antonio Tobias, bishop of Pagadian diocese, made the
charge during the funeral of Rev. Dionisio Malalay. He was gunned
down April 6 in the nearby Mindanao island town of Tabina along
with Rufino Rivera, a town councilman.
   Police say they were slain by a soldier and an anti-communist
militiaman, both of whom were drunk.
   Priests say the killings illustrate the abuses suffered by
civilians at the hands of an unruly military. Military officials
say the two victims were killed during an argument and that the
case had nothing to do with politics.
   The military faces insurgencies by both Communist and Moslem
guerrillas on Mindanao island. In December, Amnesty International
reported a ``pattern of torture'' and human rights violations by
military and paramilitary units as part of their campaign against
communist rebels.
   Tobias said nine priests and lay workers have been slain in the
Philippines since 1987. He said church officials in this
predominately Roman Catholic country have suffered harassment and
intimidation through ``propaganda, lies and threats to their very
lives.''
   He claimed the military had branded human rights activists,
priests and social workers as communists on flimsy evidence. Such
people ``can be summarily executed by military forces,'' he said.
   ``It becomes relatively clear why we consider ourselves to be
living in a period of church persecution in the Philippines,'' he
said during the services in this Mindanao island community 470
miles south of Manila.
   Constable 2nd Class Sabino Colipano, a member of the 462nd
Philippine Constabulary company, and his cousin Nelson Colipano, a
member of a local civilian militia unit, have been arrested in the
killings. The charges were brought at the urging of local church
officials.
   The bishop said he would write Mrs. Aquino, a Catholic, urging
her to order an investigation.
   ``While President Aquino is being made more and more aware of
the terrible human rights record of her government, she does not
seem to fully accept the reality,'' the bishop said.
</TEXT>
