<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-EthnicGlance     04-15 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ethnic Glance,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reforms Lift Lid on Ethnic Pandora's Box</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Divisions, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's easing of the reins that kept
the Soviet Union's 15 republics under Moscow's strict control for
decades has released pent-up anger. The central government's new
tolerance has resulted in demonstrations, strikes and political
moves unheard of before Gorbachev came to power in 1985.
   Here is a list of some of the ethnic hotspots in the Soviet
Union:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GEORGIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The republic of Georgia is a major resort area and the fruit and
vegetable basket of the Soviet Union. About 70 percent of the 5.3
million people are Georgian. Among minority ethnic groups, 9
percent are Armenian, 7 percent Russian, 5 percent Azerbaijanis and
1.7 percent Abkhazian.
   Abkhazia is an ``autonomous republic'' under the authority of
Georgia. Abkhazians comprise just 15 percent or 91,000 of its total
population of 505,000, and they are outnumbered by both Georgians
and Russians in their homeland.
   Georgian activists want to break away from the Soviet Union.
   Abkhazians complain that Georgians interfere with their national
life. They want to secede from Georgia and become a 16th republic
of the Soviet Union. Some Georgian activists oppose the Abkhazians'
secession demands.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NAGORNO-KARABAKH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Nagorno-Karabakh is an ``autonomous region'' surrounded by and
under the authority of the republic of Azerbaijan. The territory's
population is 76 percent Armenian and 23 percent Azerbaijani. The
primarily Christian Armenians claim they suffer discrimination
under the rule of the Moslem Azerbaijanis and want to annex
Nagorno-Karabakh to the republic of Armenia.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BALTIC STATES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The three Baltic states _ Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia _ were
provinces of czarist Russia before World War I and independent
nations between the world wars. They became part of the Soviet
Union in 1940, but this incorporation has not been universally
recognized.
   Movements in all three have been calling for autonomy.
   The Baltic republic of Estonia on Nov. 16 issued a ``declaration
of sovereignty'' from the central Moscow government in all areas
but defense and foreign policy. It also approved an amendment to
the republic's constitution requiring Estonian approval of all new
Soviet laws.
   Lithuania declared Lithuanian its official language and restored
the flag of the state that was independent before World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
