<SECOND>AM-Brite,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKFIELD, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of campaigning, Dick Martin
still needed a lucky draw of the cards to win another term as
village president.
   Martin turned up the king of hearts at Thursday night's Village
Board meeting to win a deadlocked race.
   His challenger, Mike Hayes, drew the jack of hearts but vowed to
seek a recount.
   He didn't mention a reshuffle.
   ``I felt very uncomfortable choosing a card to fill a government
position,'' Hayes said. ``I don't agree with it, but it's the law.''
   Martin and Hayes both received 97 votes in the April 4 election.
Under state law, the winner was to be determined by lot.
   ``I've been the clerk for 35 years and this is the first time
we've had a tie for anything like this,'' said Joyce Krueger.
   Martin, village president for four years, said after his
victory: ``Every vote counts, as this situation testifies. Let's
get back to work.''
</TEXT>
