<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-PrintingPress     04-15 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Printing Press,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Holds Printing Press For Unofficial Journal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British religious activist said Saturday that
Soviet customs officials have impounded a printing press that he
attempted to bring into the Soviet Union for an unofficial
Christian publication.
   The Rev. Dick Rodgers of Birmingham, England, said the small
offset press that he brought to the Soviet Union on Friday was
being held at Moscow's Sheremetyevo airport pending a decision by
the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
   The importation of the press for former political prisoner
Alexander Ogorodnikov's Bulletin of Christian Opinion would help in
the publishing of private journals that have sprung up in the freer
atmosphere fostered by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   Three former political prisoners _ Ogorodnikov, Lev Timofeyev
and Sergei Grigoryants _ used carbon paper and manual typewriters
when they started publishing two years ago. They have since
imported microcomputers and have gained access to tightly
controlled photocopy machines.
   Timofeyev publishes the journal Referendum, and Grigoryants
publishes Glasnost. Dozens of others publish smaller and more
limited journals.
   Officials refuse to recognize their publishing activities, and
the private publishers have no access to state-run printing
facilities.
   ``I think it is vitally important that people should be free to
publish religious literature,'' Rodgers said in a telephone
interview from Ogorodnikov's editorial office. ``If there is no
freedom to do that, then any freedom is very partial.''
   He said he decided to try to import the press, which can produce
several thousand printed sheets per hour, to test Soviet compliance
with agreements signed in Vienna earlier this year on security and
cooperation in Europe.
   Rodgers quoted the documents as saying the agreement ``allows
individuals, institutions and organizations, while respecting
intellecutal property rights including copyright, to obtain,
possess, reproduce and distribute information material of all
kinds.''
   He said Soviet customs officials took custody of it and said
they would hold onto it until they received permission to release
it from the Internal Affairs Ministry, Rodgers said.
   Rodgers said he planned to press Soviet officials in Moscow this
week for release of the press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
