<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-MafiaTrial     04-15 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mafia Trial,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Court Convicts Six In Murders, Lets off Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury on Saturday ended a Mafia trial of
121 people by convicting six men of murder but acquitting a
defendant identified as the former leader of Sicily's most powerful
mob family.
   The jury also convicted 33 other people and acquitted 81 others.
   It was Palermo's third mass trial involving the Mafia. The first
and largest of the so-called ``maxi'' trials ended in 1987 with
convictions of 338 of the 456 defendants.
   One of those acquitted Saturday was Michele ``the Pope'' Greco,
who is already serving time on another conviction and has been
identified by prosecutors as the former head of the Corleone
family. The group is considered as the most powerful Mafia clan on
the island.
   Saturday's acquittals suggested that the jury, which included
the judge, did not accept prosecutors' allegations that six murders
in question were ordered by a ``cupola,'' or executive commission,
of the Mafia. Prosecutors said Greco led that group.
   The charges were based in large part on testimony from a top
Mafioso-turned-informer, Tommaso Buscetta. His accounts helped
convict Greco and other leading Mafia figures in earlier trials.
   The new convictions came after 10 days of deliberation in the
nearly yearlong trial at Palermo's criminal court. The six men were
sentenced to life in prison.
   The mass trials grew out of an investigation into the 1982
slaying of Gen. Carlo Alberto Dalla Chiesa. He was gunned down with
his wife and bodyguard three months after he was sent to Sicily to
lead the nation's fight against the Mafia.
   Greco is serving a life sentence since his conviction in the
first trial for ordering the general's assassination.
   The trial that ended Saturday covered other murders, including
that of a local politician shot to death with a companion outside
Palermo in 1982.
   Investigators say Greco has now been replaced by Salvatore Riina
as leader of the Corleone family.
   Riina and his top lieutenant, Bernardo Provenzano, both
fugitives for decades, were tried in absentia in the latest trial
and acquitted of the murders.
   Also acquitted was Pippo Calo, another previously convicted
Mafia boss. His nickname, ``The Cashier,'' reflected his alleged
handling of profits from the mob's multimillion-dollar drug
trafficking.
   In Saturday's verdict, the 33 other people were convicted on
charges including drug trafficking and Mafia association. Six of
them were sentenced to between 14 and 22 years in jail, and the
rest face terms of up to nine years.
   During the trial, three of the original defendants died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
