<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-StadiumDisasters     04-15 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stadium Disasters,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hillsborough Site Of Europe's Worst Soccer Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stadium Collapse, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WARSHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crush that killed at least 93 people at a
Sheffield stadium Saturday was Britain's worst sports disaster and
the latest in a catalogue of calamities that have hit the world's
most popular spectator sport.
   The biggest loss of life at a soccer game occurred May 24, 1964,
when rioting left nearly 300 dead and 500 injured after Argentina
beat Peru on a last-minute goal in Lima.
   Just over a year ago, on March 12, 1988, at least 93 people died
when fans fleeing a hailstorm stampeded into locked stadium exits
in Katmandu, Nepal. More than 100 were injured.
   In 1969, soccer even caused a military conflict when El Salvador
and Honduras suffered thousands of casualties in the so-called
``Soccer War,'' which began after a disputed soccer game between
the two nations.
   The worst single-incident sports disaster anywhere in the world
in recent history occurred when an estimated 604 people were killed
after stands at the Hong Kong Jockey Club racetrack collapsed and
caught fire in February 1918.
   But soccer, the sport watched by millions of spectators from
Scandinavia to South America, has born the brunt of most sports
disasters.
   On March 10, 1987, as many as 20 people were killed when panicky
soccer fans in Tripoli, Libya, fled knife-wielding ruffians and
triggered the collapse of a wall.
   Before Saturday's shocking scenes at Hillsborough stadium in
Sheffield, Britain's worst sports disaster was at Ibrox stadium in
Glasgow in Jan. 2, 1971 when 66 soccer fans died and 170 were
injured after barriers collapsed.
   Fire caused another disaster May 11, 1985, when 56 people were
killed at Bradford, in northern England. Fire, ignited by a
cigarette stub, sparked a fire in the stadium's wooden terracing.
   That was the worst year in the history of soccer's tarnished
image.
   Eighteen days later, on May 29, 1985, 39 people, most of them
Italians, were killed in a stampede by Liverpool fans at the
European Champions Cup final at the Heysel stadium in Brussels.
   As a result, English soccer clubs were banned indefinitely by
the Union of European Football Associations, Europe's governing
body. Last week, UEFA announced it would lift the ban for the
1990-91 season, pending a review next April.
   Saturday's disaster again involved Liverpool backers. But this
time, overcrowding rather than riots appeared to be the cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
