<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     04-15 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women's Conference Against Gas Disaster Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 women gathered Saturday to
discuss the rehabilitation of survivors of the 1984 Bhopal gas
disaster and protest a legal settlement of damages decreed by
India's Supreme Court.
   The two-day convention was organized by the Bhopal Women Gas
Victims Organization, which says the $470 million settlement
decreed by India's highest court is too little.
   The government says more than 3,400 people died and at least
20,000 were injured when methyl isocyanate gas escaped from a tank
at the Bhopal pesticide plant operated by an Indian subisidary of
Union Carbide Corp., a Danbury, Conn.-based multinational.
   ``This convention is the first step to start a mass movement in
the country to fight for the rights of the gas victims,'' said
Abdul Jabbar Khan, an activist who heads the women's group.
   He predicted the convention would pass resolutions demanding a
review of the settlement and the reopening of the government's $3
billion suit against Union Carbide.
   On Feb. 14, the high court ordered Union Carbide to pay $470
million to settle all claims.
   At the convention's opening session, Dr. Sathyamala of the
Medico Friends Circle disputed the government's casualty toll for
the disaster. She said statistics collected from burial and
cremation grounds indicated at least 20,000 people died from
exposure to the gas that seeped out of the pesticide plant on Dec.
3, 1984.
   Similar claims have been made before. Given the haste with which
Hindu victims were cremated and Moslem victims were buried in
keeping with the tenets of their faiths, the precise number of
deaths may never be known.
   Dr. Sathyamala, who uses only one name, also said Bhopal's birth
rate had fallen because people who were exposed to the gas had
conception and sterility problems.
   ``The number of births has come down every year from 12,000
before the tragedy to just 7,800 now,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
