<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-US     04-15 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Protest Expulsion of Trade Representative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union strongly protested the expulsion
of a Soviet trade representative from the United States and hinted
to the U.S. ambassador in Moscow it might respond in kind, Tass
said Saturday.
   The Foreign Ministry delivered the protest to U.S. Ambassador
Jack Matlock Friday, Tass said.
   ``It was pointed out to the U.S. ambassador that the American
side would bear full responsibility for possible consequences and
that the incident remained open,'' said Tass, the official Soviet
news agency.
   On March 23, the State Department ordered Sergei Malinin, an
employee of the Soviet trade organization Amtorg, to leave the
United States. Asked if Malinin had been engaged in espionage,
State Department spokesman Charles Redman said simply he was a
persona non grata.
   Tass said U.S. authorities expelled Malinin in retaliation for
the allegedly groundless explusion by Moscow of a U.S. military
attache, Lt. Col. Daniel Francis Van Gundy, earlier in March. Van
Gundy's expulsion came a week after the arrest by the FBI of a
Soviet military attache in Washington accused by the FBI of
espionage.
   The Soviets charged Van Gundy with secretly photographing
military sites and trying to enter a closed area. Tass said U.S.
officials were given ``concrete proof of the incompatibility of the
behavior of Van Gundy and his diplomatic status.''
   Tass said Matlock was told Malinin's expulsion conflicted with
the warmer trend in Soviet-U.S. relations.
</TEXT>
