<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     04-15 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Romania Has Nuclear Weapons Potential</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu has
acknowleged publicly his country has the potential to make nuclear
weapons, according to media reports Saturday.
   Ceausescu also said Romania would ban new hard currency
borrowings now that it has repaid its $21 billion foreign debt,
according to the state news agency Agerpres, monitored in Vienna.
   ``We can produce any equipment and machinery, let us be
competitive with the best products turned out in the world,''
Agerpres quoted him as saying.
   ``In only one domain we do not want to do it _ that of nuclear
weapons. Technically, we have this ability as well, but ... we are
firmly resolved to fight against nuclear weapons,'' Ceausescu
reportedly told the Socialist Democracy and Unity Front, a
Communist-led organization.
   The statement followed unconfirmed reports that Ceausescu
mentioned Romania's nuclear capability to Hungarian Communist party
leader Karoly Grosz at an August meeting in the Romanian town of
Arad.
   The Agerpres report gave no further details of the statement on
nuclear weapons by Ceausescu, who has ruled his country since 1965.
   In a separate speech Friday concluding the three-day Communist
Party Central Committee session, Ceausescu said he will submit to
parliament a law that ``nobody should be allowed in any form to
resort to any foreign credit.''
   Such a law would put Romania on par with Albania, the only other
European nation whose laws forbid borrowing from the West.
   When he opened the session Wednesday, Ceausescu announced
Romania had paid off its foreign debt with western creditors.
   Excerpts of the speech reported by Agerpres showed Ceausescu
firmly rejecting Soviet-style reforms of Communism and announcing
plans to revise current Romanian editions of works by Karl Marx,
Friedrich Engels and Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin.
   The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug, reporting on the Central
Committee meeting from Bucharest, said it reaffirmed controversial
plans to destroy villages in Romania and also rejected recent
Western criticism of human rights abuses in Romania.
   Ceausescu said last year that 7,000 villages might be destroyed
in a scheme to create large agro-industrial complexes in the
countryside, once the backbone of Romania's agriculture-based
economy.
   Severe food shortages have developed in recent years as the
emphasis has switched to industry, and agricultural produce was
exported to the Soviet bloc in exchange for raw materials and to
the West for hard currency.
   The hard currency was needed to pay off Romania's debt.
</TEXT>
