<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     04-15 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Plenum Meets to Prepare Party Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party will campaign as the
``initiator of reforms'' in parliamentary elections, its spokesman
said following a political strategy meeting on Saturday.
   Spokesman Jan Bisztyga announced 1,749 party delegates will
attend a party convention next month to approve candidates and
positions. He also said the party was considering whether members
will be allowed to join a legal Solidarity trade union.
   ``During this election campaign, we would like society to learn
more about the party as the initiator of reforms,'' Bisztyga told a
news conference after the brief party meeting. ``We would like to
prove that the party stands behind the reforms.''
   The meeting of the 230-member party Central Committee was the
first since communist authorities and the opposition agreed April 5
to hold partially free elections to parliament and restore the
legal status of Solidarity _ the Soviet bloc's first independent
trade union.
   The party's first secretary, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, opened
and closed the meeting at party headquarters, the official PAP news
agency reported.
   A brief PAP statement said the Central Committee took decisions
on the parliamentary elections and May 4-5 party conference.
   He said the party was considering whether to allow its 2.3
million members to join Solidarity. The trade movement applied for
legal registration Thursday, and it is expected to be granted
Monday.
   Jaruzelski's decision to accept a legal Solidarity was adopted
only after a stormy party meeting in mid-January.
   Legalizing Solidarity marks a reversal in the party's attitude
toward the opposition, which it had tried to eliminate for seven
years after a December 1981 martial-law crackdown.
   Saturday's meeting also debated party campaign strategy in the
parliamentary elections. The elections are scheduled in two stages:
the first stage on June 4 and a runoff vote June 18.
   The elections will be the first time in the history of the
communist state that candidates can run for parliament without
first having been approved by the party.
   Under the new electoral law, the party and its allies will be
guaranteed 65 percent of the seats in the 460-member Sejm, the
present one-house parliament, with the other 35 percent to be
openly contested by independent, non-party candidates. All seats of
the new 100-member Senate are to be freely contested between
communists and independents.
   Bisztyga said the division of seats among the communist party
and its allies, the Peasants' Party and the Democratic Party, was
under discussion and would be announced before an April 25 deadline
set by the Council of State.
</TEXT>
