<FIRST>r i AM-Concorde     04-15 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Concorde,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Concorde Leaves Australia _ With New Tail Part</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A repaired Concorde jet roared away from
Australia on Saturday to attempt a supersonic speed record, leaving
investigators baffled about why part of its tail tore off over the
ocean last week.
   ``There are no signs of metal fatigue,'' said British Airways
airport services manager Pat Boody. ``Engineers have crawled all
over it, replaced the tail assembly, and we still don't know why it
happened.''
   On Wednesday, the British Airways plane lost a four-by-three
foot chunk of its tail over the South Pacific while setting a speed
record from Christchurch, New Zealand. Though the 100 American
passengers aboard felt a shudder, the crew served lunch and the
plane landed safely in Sydney with no injuries reported.
   It was traveling about 1,500 mph at the time, nearly twice the
speed of sound.
   Capt. David Leney, the pilot, said earlier in the week he was
puzzled why the Concorde lost part of its tail.
   ``We were climbing at 44,000 feet when there was a slight
bump,'' Leney said. ``I didn't know at the time we had lost part of
the rudder. I thought we must have hit something. But how can that
be at 44,000 feet? There's nothing there to hit us.''
   Despite the incident, the passengers, many of whom are wealthy,
seemed to have few worries about reboarding the in Sydney earlier
Saturday for the flight to Perth in western Australia. It made a
one-hour refueling stop and continued on to Colombo, Sri Lanka.
   The plane is on a three-week odyssey that started April 1 in
London. It is trying to establish supersonic speed records on each
of 12 legs of its around-the-world journey that ends in London on
April 23.
   The Concorde, which also performs regular commercial service,
has been used mainly on transatlantic routes.
   Boody said a seven-member repair team flew in from London and
worked around the clock so the jet could leave only one day behind
schedule for Perth and Sri Lanka.
   The Concorde completed the Sydney-Perth trip, a distance of
about 2,050 miles, in two hours, 40 minutes and 5 seconds. It
reached a maximum speed of 1,300 mph.
   ``You would be a fool to miss this,'' said passenger Tony
Misciagna, an investments broker from Altoona, Pa. Like others on
the trip, he paid $39,000 for the 38,215-mile journey.
   ``We're ... going to places we wouldn't normally go because it
usually takes so long,'' he said. ``It's got to be the best bargain
in town. I'm going to go again next year, even if its costs more.''
</TEXT>
