<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt     04-15 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Flexes Muscle by Ousting Defense Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak on Saturday removed
Defense Minister Abdel-Halim Abu-Ghazala, who was viewed as the
government's No. 2 man, and named him to a largely ceremonial post.
   The government described the transfer of Abu-Ghazala to the
assistant presidency as a promotion, but diplomats said it was a
demotion. They said it underscored Mubarak's control of the
government.
   The post of assistant president, now vacant, has been largely
ceremonial.
   Abu-Ghazala helped develop Egypt's strong ties with the United
States. The development took U.S. officials here by surprise, but
one Western diplomat said it should not hurt U.S.-Egyptian
relations.
   ``I understand they're in a frenzy,'' he said of U.S. officials,
``but I wouldn't have thought that the passing of Abu-Ghazala
should necessarily worry the Americans.
   ``He's very pro-American, but there are a lot of people like
that in the Egyptian forces,'' the diplomat said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The country's political system is closer to democracy than that
of almost any other Arab state, but it maintains equilibrium
through the use of police and military force. Many people have
assumed Mubarak relied on the army and generals like Abu-Ghazala as
a prop for his authority.
   ``I suppose the main significance is that Mubarak felt strong
enough to do it. He very clearly must have had the backing of the
armed forces,'' the diplomat said.
   The U.S. Embassy staff had no immediate reaction.
   The ambassador added that he had long heard rumors that Mubarak
was unhappy with Abu-Ghazala's personal and professional ethical
standards.
   But Abu-Ghazala, a 59-year-old with five children, is reported
to have taken a second wife, less than half the age of his first
after a public courtship that scandalized some Eygptians, according
to government and diplomatic sources. Moslems may take up to four
wives.
   In addition, Westerners who do business with the Defense
Ministry also speak of significant corruption.
   The last assistant president was former Prime Minister Mamdouh
Salem. He died three years ago, and the position has been vacant
since then.
   The post is separate from the vice presidency, which is also
vacant. The country has had no vice president since Mubarak
succeeded assassinated President Anwar Sadat in October 1981.
Mubarak served as vice president to Sadat from 1975 until the
assassination.
   In the last few years, there have been frequent reports and
speculation that Mubarak would promote Abu-Ghazala to vice
president. Abu-Ghazala denied the reports.
   The Defense Ministry, which Abu-Ghazala headed for eight years,
will now be operated by Maj. Gen. Youssef Sabry Abu-Taleb, 60, who
ran Cairo's government for six years as governor.
   Mubarak announced the two appointments in decrees and
immediately swore in the two men to their new posts Saturday.
   Afterward, Prime Minister Atef Sedki told reporters only that
Mubarak ``needs at his side someone to help him in the huge tasks
that he has to discharge.''
   However, government sources pointed out that Abu-Taleb, not
Abu-Ghazala, accompanied Mubarak on a trip to Jordan on Wednesday
to discuss with King Hussein his upcoming U.S. trip. The sources
said Abu-Ghazala was removed from the delegation at the last minute.
   Abu-Ghazala, 59, served as military attache in Washington
between 1976 and 1979. He was regarded as a prime player in forging
Cairo's special relationship with the United States after Egypt
signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979.
   He was graduated from Cairo's Military Academy in 1949, but he
later attended military courses both in the Soviet Union and the
United States. He was an officer in Egypt's 1956, 1967 and 1973
wars with Israel.
   The Middle East News Agency said Mahmoud Sherif, governor of
Sharkia province, would take over as governor of Cairo.
  
</TEXT>
