<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RitualSlayings-Movie     04-15 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings-Movie,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police: Bizarre Cult Was Inspired by Movie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ritual Slayings-Clues, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bizarre sect of suspected drug
smugglers was influenced by a cult movie called ``The Believers''
about the time they began performing human sacrifices to protect
their illegal business, police said Saturday.
   The 1986 movie, starring Martin Sheen and directed by John
Schlesinger, is about rich, influential families who protect their
prominence with rites including human sacrifice.
   The motives of the movie's characters are chillingly similar to
those of the members of the real-life cult accused of sacrificing
at least 13 people on a ranch west of Matamoros, Mexico, police
said.
   ``They keep bringing the movie up,'' Cameron County Sheriff's
Lt. George Gavito said after interviewing two suspects. ``They talk
about it like that had something to do with changing them.''
   The 13 bodies were found this week on a ranch 20 miles west of
Matamoros, across the Rio Grande from Brownsville. Police said most
of the cult's victims died either from blows dealt with a machete
or a hammer.
   Some suffered horrible mutilations, including the removal of
brains, hearts and other organs that were boiled with blood in what
suspects have described as sacrificial rites of a cult seeking
magical protection for their drug-smuggling activities.
   Authorities said the gang smuggled a ton of marijuana a week
into the United States.
   Four suspects are in custody, all in Matamoros. Four others _
including a man and woman whom sect members called ``the
godfather'' and ``the godmother'' _ are at large.
   U.S. federal authorities videotaped interviews Friday with two
of the suspects in custody in Matamoros, said Oran Neck, agent in
charge of U.S. Customs in Brownsville.
   Serafin Hernandez Garcia and Elio Hernandez Rivera told the U.S.
officials the cult's ``godmother,'' Sara Maria Aldrete, recruited
them into the group early 1988, Neck said.
   Ms. Aldrete, 24, and the cult's Cuban-born leader, Adolfo de
Jesus Constanzo, 26, at first practiced a widespread Afro-Cuban
religion called Santeria, or ``the way of the saints,'' the
suspects told authorities. Santeria assigns Roman Catholic saints
with the characteristics of West African deities. Like many
religions originating among poor, farming people, Santeria
sometimes calls for the sacrifice of animals, but never humans.
   But the group's relatively benign rites turned sinister late
last summer, about the time Ms. Aldrete began urging members to
watch videotapes of ``The Believers,'' Gavito said.
   The movie did not in itself incite group members to perform
human sacrifice, Gavito said, but it reinforced their desire to
begin killing people to provide a magical shield for their alleged
drug activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890415-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 1740EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-HuYaobang 1stLd-Writethru a0509 04-15 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Hu Yaobang, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hu Yaobang, Reformer and Former Communist Leader, Dies At 73</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with university students praising
Hu, government statement. Pick up 10th pvs, `The chain-smoking...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hu Yaobang, an outspoken reformer who led the
world's largest Communist Party until a 1987 purge consigned him to
political oblivion, died of heart failure Saturday. He was 73.
   The protege of senior leader Deng Xiaoping died one week after
he suffered a heart attack during a meeting of the Politburo, the
ruling body that dismissed him as party general secretary two years
before.
   At Beijing University, hundreds of students put up posters
praising Hu as a reformer and indirectly criticizing those who
ousted him.
   The Chinese Communist Party he led for seven years described Hu
as a ``great proletarian revolutionary'' and ``loyal communist
fighter'' who led a glorious life with ``everlasting merits for the
party and the people.''
   But Hu suffered from his party's swift ideological shifts.
   He joined Mao Tse-tung on the 1934-35 Long March but was
targeted by Mao's Red Guards during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution, spending nearly the entire decade banished to the
countryside or under house arrest.
   Hu's political fortunes rose after Mao's death, and he helped
revive China's economy through market-oriented reforms. He once
stood on the threshold of succeeding Deng Xiaoping as the leader of
China's 1.1 billion people, but he fell from grace over 1986
pro-democracy student demonstrations.
   He was forced to resign on Jan. 16, 1987 after being blamed for
failing to put down the demonstrations. Hu, who had reportedly
alienated Deng with his outspoken manner, also was accused of
promoting dangerously high growth rates and neglecting to stop the
trend toward Westernization.
   Hu retained his seat on the powerful 17-member Politburo, but he
made no public statements and appeared ill at ease in his few
public appearances.
   He was last seen during the annual session of China's
parliament, the National People's Congress, which ended April 4.
   At Beijing University Saturday, hundreds of students milled
around posters praising Hu as a ``leading force in reform.'' One
poster referred obliquely to Hu's 1987 ouster as ``that year when
you were made to play the scapegoat.''
   ``May your spirit re-awaken to bear witness to history,''
another poster said, in an apparent call for a review of the
charges against him.
   The evening television news briefly played mournful music while
displaying a picture of Hu, then read a Communist Party statement
that praised Hu as a statesman and ``great proletarian
revolutionary.''
   The statement did not mention Hu's ouster in disgrace.
   The chain-smoking Hu, Deng's longtime bridge partner, was widely
expected to take over Deng's functions when China's senior leader,
now 84, stepped down.
   The unofficial scenario called for Hu, once he overcame the
suspicions of the conservative military, to take over Deng's posts
and become the nation's undisputed leader. Instead, former Premier
Zhao Ziyang succeeded Hu as party boss and Li Peng, who favors
economic stability over reform initiatives, became premier.
   Hu was born in November 1915 in Liuyang County, Hunan province.
According to official reports, he left home at the age of 14 to
join the Communist Party Children's Corps.
   He took part in the Long March, the Red Army's epic flight from
Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalist forces, and served as a political
commissar during the 1937-45 war against Japan.
   Hu became secretary of the Communist Youth League in 1952, three
years after Mao's forces took over the mainland, and in 1956 he was
appointed to the party Central Committee.
   In 1966, as head of the Youth League, he became a prime target
of Mao's Cultural Revolution. Red Guards shaved his head, forced
him to crawl on his hands and knees and exiled him to rural Henan
province.
   Among his alleged crimes was that he and Deng, another victim of
the leftists, used railroad cars and special airplanes to ferry
bridge partners around the country.
   Hu was rehabilitated in 1977 and headed the party office in
charge of redressing injustice during the Cultural Revolution.
   He quickly rankled party ideologues, men who would later push
for his ouster, by criticizing Mao for his role in the Cultural
Revolution, which he described as a ``period of catastrophe'' in
which ``nothing was correct or positive.''
   He was elected secretary general of the party Central Committee
in 1980, and served as chairman of the party from June 1981 until
the title was abolished in September 1982. He then became general
secretary of the party.
   Hu had four children and five grandchildren. His wife Li Zhao is
a clothing designer and former official in the Beijing Textile
Bureau.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890415-0086 </DOCNO>
