<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Abortion     04-15 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Abortion,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March To Support Abortion Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people marched through downtown
Rome Saturday to support the availability of abortion and protest
what they called restrictions in Italy's abortion law.
   State police said at least 35,000 people took part in the
demonstration, but the paramilitary Carabinieri put the number at
60,000 and organizers claimed 200,000 marched.
   Police blocked off a large area of central Rome as the
demonstrators, carrying banners reading ``We Want to Choose,''
marched along a two-mile route in intermittent rain.
   The marchers were led by women from at least eight political
parties, including Italy's second- and third-largest parties, the
Communists and Socialists.
   Many demonstrators aimed their barbs at Health Minister Carlo
Donat Cattin, a member of Italy's dominant Christian Democrat
party. An effigy carried by one group caricatured Donat Cattin as
``minister of chastity.''
   Donat Cattin has been at the center of the dispute over Italy's
1978 abortion law. It allows first-trimester abortions only in
public hospitals and permits doctors to refuse to perform the
procedure by declaring themselves conscientious objectors.
   Pro-abortion activists say women are forced to undergo dangerous
illegal abortions because too many doctors use the exemption. They
say that according to one estimate, two-thirds of Italy's doctors
have declared themselves objectors.
   Religious leaders and conservatives have joined Donat Cattin in
seeking more restrictions in the abortion law. Anti-abortion
activists say the law is being abused and that some women are
undergoing abortions in the fifth month of pregnancy.
</TEXT>
