<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionPoll     04-15 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Poll,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>77 Percent Say Abortion Should Be Legal At Least Conditonally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than three-quarters of Americans approve of
abortion under some circumstances, according to a Gallup poll
released Saturday.
   The poll, conducted for Newsweek magazine after last week's huge
abortion rights rally in Washington, found 27 percent of those
asked said abortion should be legal without conditions, the highest
percentage since the Gallup Organization first asked the question
in 1975.
   Another 50 percent said they approved of abortion only under
certain circumstances, which were not specified in the question.
Only 18 percent of Americans surveyed believe abortion should be
illegal without exceptions.
   Fifty-one percent said they do not want the Supreme Court to
overturn Roe v. Wade, the 1973 decision that legalized abortion.
   The Gallup organization interviewed a national sample of 750
adults on April 12 and 13. The rally was held April 9. The margin
of error is plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</TEXT>
