<HEAD>Libya Defends Acquisition of Soviet Bombers, Denounces U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya on Saturday denounced the United States and
Secretary of State James A. Baker III for criticizing Libya's
acquisition of Soviet fighter-bombers.
   An article by the political editor of Libya's official JANA news
agency said:
   ``If Baker deplores the possession by Jamahiriya (Libya) of some
equipment it needs to exercise its self-defense, how does he
justify his government's supply of a very advanced arsenal of
military equipment to the Zionist enemy (Israel), used in attacking
the Palestinian Arab people and disturbing the stability of the
whole region... ?''
   It said Libya has ``reasserted its clear stance rejecting all
forms and types of terrorism, and world public opinion ... no
longer believes such fabricated accusations promoted by hostile
forces either through their statements or leaked reports.'' The
report was monitored in Rome.
   U.S. officials have said the Soviets supplied Libya with up to
15 Sukhoi fighter-bombers capable of threatening Egypt and possibly
Israel.
   But Soviet officials said no more than six such planes were sent
to Libya and they are defensive aircraft.
   The JANA article made no mention of U.S. air raids three years
ago on the Libyan cities of Tripoili and Benghazi. The Reagan
administration said the bombings on April 15, 1986 were carried out
because Libya supports international terrorism.
