<FIRST>r a AM-FatherDamien     04-15 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Father Damien,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Honor Belgian Priest Who Ministered to Hawaii Leper Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAUPAPA, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Father Damien de Veuster, who
ministered to lepers on this remote peninsula a century ago, was
remembered Saturday by hundreds still moved by his compassion for
society's outcasts.
   Some flew in by airplane and others hiked down imposing cliffs
that isolate the Kalawao Hansen's Disease settlement on Molokai
Island to participate in ceremonies marking the centennial of the
Belgian priest's death.
   Guests including Prince Philippe of Belgium, Hawaii Gov. John
Waihee and members of the de Veuster family from Tremeloo, Belgium,
gathered at St. Philomena Church, better known as ``Father Damien's
Church.''
   Damien came to Hawaii in 1873 and served at Kalaupapa for 16
years before dying of Hansen's Disease, or leprosy, at the age of
49. He not only attended to spiritual needs, but treated patients
and helped construct houses and churches for the settlement.
   The Catholic Church has been declared Damien ``venerable,'' one
of the final phases in the process culminating with elevation to
sainthood.
   ``He was the face, the voice and the light of hope for the
hundreds of the abandoned banished to this remote place by terror
of what was then a loathsome disease,'' Waihee said.
   Prince Philippe said Damien helped bring the ``heartbreaking
physical and moral misery'' of Hansen's Disease to world attention.
   The windswept peninsula, bounded by 1,600-foot cliffs and rough
seas, is still home to about 90 Hansen's Disease patients. The site
is now a national park.
</TEXT>
