<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-Reformers     04-15 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Reformers,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Reformers Gather At Unprecedented Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KECSKEMET, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's leading communist reformers
met Saturday for an unprecedented debate on the future of the
governing Communist Party and a possible split.
   The meeting came three days after the Communist Party shuffled
the leadership of its ruling Politburo.
   Imre Pozsgay, one of the most prominent reformers, told some 600
people at the meeting that a split in the party would mean its
demise. But others said the party might be ineffective without a
drastic change.
   There had been speculation before Wednesday's shakeup in the
Politburo that the reformers might break with the party.
   Pozsgay said a multiparty system is ``unavoidable'' and the
Communist Party must take the lead in solving social and economic
problems if it wants to compete.
   ``Let's endeavor to account for our deeds before we are called
to account,'' he said.
   According to published reports, many of the thousands of people
who have left the party in the past year were dissatisfied with the
slow pace of reforms.
   Reszo Nyers, a reformer and a Politburo member, said sweeping
economic changes such as the introduction of market forces are
crucial but they could not be achieved by a single party, ``even if
it is a reform party.''
   Pal Vashtag, a reformer who became a member of the Politburo on
Wednesday, told journalists that a split in the party would be
``highly unfortunate.''
   During the debate, however, some participants advocated a split.
   ``Enforced unity only paralyzes the effectiveness of the party,
which forces it to make compromises and make effective leadership
impossible,'' said Csaba Gombar, a political scientist.
   Two speakers who received strong applause were Laszlo Lengyel
and Mihaly Bihari, both expelled from the party a year ago.
   Lengyel said ``Hungarian society will simply bypass the ...
party if it continues to avoid the hard decisions.''
   Bihari said procedures for a multiparty system must be
established as soon as possible.
</TEXT>
