<FIRST>r i AM-PuertoRico     04-15 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Marshals and Navy Blocked by Vieques Residents Over Eviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of residents of Vieques
Island camped out Saturday around the house of a family ordered to
leave land that the U.S. Navy claims is federal property.
   Two Navy vehicles were burned Friday when about 100 neighbors of
Carmelo Felix Matta blocked an attempt by three U.S. marshals to
enforce an eviction order. No injuries were reported.
   The Navy claims Felix Matta, an unemployed veteran living on a
Veterans Administration pension, and his family are ``unauthorized
occupants'' of land within the boundaries of Camp Garcia, located
on Vieques Island.
   The 32-square-mile island is off the east coast of Puerto Rico.
   Lt. Richard Boyle, a spokesman for Navy operations in the
Caribbean, said Saturday the Navy has been trying to get Felix
Matta and an unspecified number of other families off the land
since 1985.
   The San Juan Star newspaper said that when Felix Matta refused
the marshals' order to leave on Friday, the officers called for
assistance from the Navy.
   Eight sailors arrived in two trucks and began loading the
vehicles with items from Felix Matta's house. Area residents then
blocked the road, and someone threw gasoline on the trucks and set
them afire, the newspaper said.
   The residents returned many of the family's belongings to the
house, according to the newspaper.
   A person at the scene Saturday said the Matta family remained in
the house and dozens of residents were camped out at the site in
case of another eviction attempt.
   Charles Connelly, publisher of The Vieques Times, a monthly
newsletter, said the Felix Matta house is about two miles from the
entrance to Camp Garcia and about 2,000 feet from the fence
surrounding the base.
   He said the Navy contends that although the house is outside the
fence, it is in a buffer zone established in 1985 between the fence
and civilian property.
   ``Recently the Navy began hanging signs in front of houses, some
of which are businesses, saying they are on U.S. federal
property,'' Connelly said.
   He said Felix Matta has been on the land since at least 1976.
   Two-thirds of Vieques Island, located between Puerto Rico and
the U.S. Virgin Islands, is owned by the Navy. The U.S. military
uses a large section as a bombing and gunnery range.
   There have been sporadic protests of the Navy presence and
bombing range. In the early 1980s commercial fishermen defied the
Navy and entered restricted waters during military maneuvers.
   About 7,000 people live on Vieques, and many are fishermen.
</TEXT>
