<HEAD>Susini Sculpture Auctioned For $3.3 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bronze sculpture by 17th century Italian artist
Francesco Susini, ``The Kidnapping of Helen by Paris,'' sold at
auction Saturday for $3.3 million, more than double the amount that
had been expected.
   The sculpture, completed in Florence in 1627, was once in the
collection of Jean-Baptiste Machault d'Arnouville, controller of
finances for Louis XV. It had been exhibited by his descendents at
the Chateau de Thoiry outside Paris.
   The sale was conducted by auctioneer Jacques Tajan at the Hotel
George V in Paris. The purchaser was not identified.
   The sculpture is 27{ inches high and portrays standing male and
female figures representing Paris and Helen of Troy with a third
figure at their feet, a servant trying to stop the abduction.
   According to myth, Helen's abduction sparked the Trojan War.
</TEXT>
