<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Jordan-Elections     04-15 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jordan-Elections,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Election Law Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein on Saturday approved a new
election law that cancels representation in the Jordanian
Parliament for the Israeli-occupied West Bank, a government source
said.
   The action builds on Hussein's decision last July to renounce
sovereignty over the West Bank in favor of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Jordan ruled the West Bank until 1967, when Israel captured the
territory during the Middle East war. Both Israel and the United
States have suggested Jordan should play a role in the West Bank as
part of any Middle East peace settlement.
   The new election law came days before Hussein's scheduled trip
to the United States. He meets with President Bush in Washington on
Wednesday.
   The law also promotes Jordan's claim to the Palestinian refugees
it has sheltered following the 1948 and 1967 civil wars by giving
them the same voting rights as other Jordanian citizens, said the
source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Hussein has said that Palestinians on the East Bank of the
Jordan River who hold Jordanian citizenship have the same duties as
other Jordanians.
   About half of Jordan's 3 million people come from Palestinian
families, although most live outside the U.N.-run refugee camps.
   Previous electoral laws gave camp residents Parliament seats
based on the number of camps rather than on the number of residents.
   No date for new elections was set.
   The source said the law calls for a 72-member lower house of
Parliament. The old 60-member Parliament was suspended in 1988.
</TEXT>
