<SECOND>AM-Fusion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0565,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breakthrough Cold Fusion Experiments Prompt Dueling MIT Theories</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-10 to clarify that Georgia test inconclusive, specify
which atoms form bonds. Pick up 11th graf, ``Some of..'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two rival theories to explain recent experiments
in nuclear fusion have emerged from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, and on them may depend the vision of a society with a
limitless supply of energy.
   One theory holds that the experiments depend primarily on a
chemical reaction, rather than a nuclear one, and offer little hope
for a clean new source of electrical power.
   The other postulates that fusion is taking place and results
from the unusual properties of the precious metal palladium and
from sub-atomic behavior known as ``quantum tunneling.'' If so, it
is at least theoretically possible the process could be harnessed
for electric power.
   The first theory is the work of MIT professor Keith H. Johnson;
the second comes from his colleague, Peter L. Hagelstein. Both men,
who have been working independently, announced Friday that they
have submitted papers describing the theories to scientific
journals.
   Chemists at the University of Utah caused a sensation last month
when they said they had found a way to merge, or fuse, the nuclei
of hydrogen atoms at room temperature.
   They said they had produced nuclear fusion in ``heavy'' water,
which contains the hydrogen isotope deuterium, in a process that
generated four times more power than it used.
   Nuclear fusion, which fuels the sun and the stars, is regarded
by scientists as having enormous potential as a clean, efficient
energy source. Unlike nuclear fission, which splits atoms, fusion
leaves little radioactive waste.
   Until the Utah announcement, scientists believed temperatures
close to 100 million degrees were necessary to overcome the
electrical forces of repulsion between atomic nuclei. Laboratories
in Texas, and in Hungary and the Soviet Union say they have
duplicated the experiment. Georgia scientists initially announced
they had successfully performed it, then said they may have erred.
   In the view of Johnson, a 52-year-old materials science
professor, the conditions used in the Utah experiment permit atoms
of hydrogen and deuterium to be tightly bound together in the
crystal lattice structure of the palladium.
   The hydrogen and deuterium atoms form chemical bonds and begin
vibrating at very high frequencies, producing heat.
   ``Some of the nuclei occasionally get close enough together that
they actually fuse, but the large bulk of the heat that is produced
is not associated with the fusion,'' he said Friday.
   ``This process not being nuclear in origin means it is not a
panacea for solving the world's energy problems,'' Johnson said.
``It will not, in my opinion, be useful for large scale energy
production.''
   Hagelstein, 34, who works in MIT's Research Laboratory of
Electronics, claims to be seeking a patent for an related fusion
process, as yet untested.
   The dominant reaction in the Utah experiment, in Hagelstein's
theory, is the fusion of two deuterium nuclei, which produces
helium and releases energy that is trapped within the palladium
lattice and eventually emerges as heat.
   The theory focuses on ``quantum tunnelling,'' an explanation for
how nuclei can overcome the electrostatic forces that ordinarily
keep them apart to fuse at lower energy levels than normally
expected.
   The use of this fusion energy to produce electrical energy
``with some efficiency'' seems likely, he wrote in an abstract of
his papers.
   Hagelstein theorized that the reaction is triggered by some
outside source, such as a cosmic ray. Some researchers may have
been unable to duplicate the Utah result because they have shielded
their experiments with materials such as lead that would block such
rays, he said.
   Scientists at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in
Livermore, Calif., and at Los Alamos Laboratory in Los Alamos,
N.M., said their initial efforts to duplicate the fusion experiment
had not been conclusive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
