<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Steloff     04-15 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Steloff,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Founder of Gotham Book Mart Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frances Steloff, whose Gotham Book Mart was the
place to browse, work and buy books for many great American
writers, died Saturday at the age of 101.
   Miss Steloff, who celebrated her birthday on New Year's Eve,
died of pneumonia at Mount Sinai Hospital, said Andreas Brown, who
succeeded her as owner of the bookstore. She had been hospitalized
for about a week, he said.
   Miss Steloff achieved ``a small miracle,'' Brown said, in
founding the Book Mart in 1920 with very little support or backing,
and sustaining it through the Depression and World War II.
   Miss Steloff's celebrated customers included Ernest Hemingway,
James Joyce, Dylan Thomas, e.e. cummings, W.H. Auden, Gertrude
Stein, Anais Nin, John Dos Passos and Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
   In a congratulatory message sent to Miss Steloff on her 100th
birthday, writer John Updike wrote, ``The Gotham Book Mart is my
favorite bookstore in North America.''
   Miss Steloff was born and reared in Saratoga Springs. Her
father, Simon Steloff, a rabbi, and her mother, Tobe, were Russian
immigrants. She was the first of their 14 children born in the
United States.
   She opened the book mart on Jan. 1, 1920, two blocks from the
present site in Manhattan's diamond district, and sold the
bookstore in 1967 to Brown, a rare book appraiser.
   The survival of Gotham was once in doubt when Miss Steloff
became involved in a legal battle over the ownership of the
bookstore's building with the American Friends of Hebrew University.
   Miss Steloff and the American Friends organization agreed to a
negotiated settlement in late February, Brown said.
   Miss Steloff is survived by her sister, Belle Sidoroff, of
Wilmington, Del., and her brother, Alex Steloff, of Saratoga
Springs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
