<FIRST>r i AM-Uruguay-Amnesty     04-15 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uruguay-Amnesty,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters To Cast Ballots In Referendum On Amnesty For Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of court hearings and
public debates Uruguayans vote Sunday to uphold or cancel an
amnesty for soldiers accused of human rights violations during the
military dictatorship.
   Congress passed an amnesty law in December 1986 that would apply
to security forces, but some political and human rights groups
quickly organized to try to overturn the measure by referendum.
   In late 1987 the anti-amnesty groups submitted petitions with
634,000 signatures to the Electoral Court. The court eventually
affirmed the required minimum of 555,701 signatures, one-fourth of
the electorate at that time.
   President Julio M. Sanguinetti, elected in November 1984 after
democracy was restored following 12 years of military rule,
supports the amnesty law.
   He said nullification of it ``would be a step backward in the
process of national pacification.''
   Parties supporting the referendum say soldiers and police
accused of kidnappings, torture and killings must be tried if
democracy is to be fully re-established.
   ``The law should be annulled not only because its content is
contrary to human rights traditionally defended in our country ...
but also for the reason that it was sanctioned and promulgated
under military threat,'' the National Commission for the Referendum
said recently.
   It is estimated that 150 people were killed and more than 200
others were arrested and disappeared during the military crackdown
on suspected left-wing subversives that began in 1973. Several
thousand Uruguayans claim they were tortured after being detained
by security forces.
   President Juan M. Bordaberry, under military pressure in 1973,
gave the armed forces a free hand to act against rebels, especially
the Tupamaros guerrillas. The military took control and ousted
Bordaberry in June 1976.
   Sanguinetti took office in March 1985. He supported an amnesty
law passed by Congress that freed political prisoners and gave jobs
back to hundreds of public employees who had been fired by the
military government.
   That law excluded the security forces, and by mid-1986 about 50
cases had been filed accusing some 180 soldiers of human rights
abuses.
   Military officials made it known that they opposed the trial of
military men in civilian courts and Sanguinetti headed off a
potential crisis by pressing for an amnesty that would include the
military. Congress passed that measure on Dec. 22, 1986.
   Polls open at 8 a.m. and close at 7:30 p.m. Those who favor the
amnesty law will cast yellow ballots and those opposed will cast
green ballots.
   There are 2.3 million eligible voters and preliminary results
are expected Sunday night.
</TEXT>
