<DOCNO> AP890415-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 2156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-RitualSlayings-Clues 2ndLd-Writethru a0558 04-15 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings-Clues, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0558,0879</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tail From Police Checkpoint Leads To Cult Horror</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Hernandez, David...,' to CORRECT name of cult
leader to Adolfo, sted Alfonso; SUBS 28th graf, `To many...,' to clarify
that city referred to is Matamoros.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANCHO SANTA ELENA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks ago Elio Hernandez
ran his pickup through a police drug checkpoint near the U.S.
border and sped on. The young man didn't worry about police
following him; he thought he was invisible.
   ``We located the place, waited a few days and then moved in,''
said federal police commander Juan Benitez Ayala.
   Police expected to make a large marijuana bust, commonplace here.
   Instead, they ripped the mask from a nightmarish world of black
magic, sex, drug smuggling and human sacrifice.
   Twelve bodies were found Tuesday and one more on Thursday,
buried near a corral. Some had their hearts ripped out, their
genitals cut off or their brains removed. Some died of machete
blows to the head. Most died blindfolded and gagged.
   Police said they had all been killed by smugglers who believed
that human sacrifice would give them a ``magical shield'' that
would protect them from the law.
   Among the victims were a 16-year-old boy and Mark Kilroy,
missing since March when he came here during spring break from the
University of Texas.
   Hernandez, David Serna, Serafin Hernandez Garcia and Sergio
Martinez were arrested. Police on Saturday sought the alleged
ringleader, a Cuban-American ``voodoo priest'' Adolfo De Jesus
Constanzo, and a ``witch,'' Sara Aldrete.
   All four defendants blamed Constanzo, whom they called the
``padrino,'' for the murders. They claimed they had been lured into
the cult by Miss Aldrete's sexual favors. Aldrete also lured some
of the victims, they said.
   Hernandez and Serna told newsmen that Constanzo, whom they had
known for nine months, had initiated them into the occult, but they
said they did not know much about it. ``We believed sometimes and
sometimes we did not,'' said Hernandez.
   A federal agent who asked not to be identified said the group
was ``totally under the control of the Cuban. I don't think they
even knew what they were getting into.''
   ``They were told that the sacrifices would protect them from
police,'' the agent said. ``One of them told us that the padrino
told him police would not see him even if they walked by him.''
   Hernandez and Hernandez Garcia are Texas natives, born in
Mission and Weslaco, respectively, in the Rio Grande Valley just
across the border. Aldrete, a Mexican citizen, was a student at
Texas Southmost College in Brownsville.
   Two days after the checkpoint incident, police picked up Domingo
Reyes, the ranch caretaker, and asked him about activities at the
100-acre ranch just below the U.S. border. Reyes started talking
about strange happenings in the wooden shack near the main ranch
house, and how he was once told not to come close.
   On a hunch, a federal agent showed him a picture of Kilroy.
   ``I saw him at the ranch one day,'' Reyes said.
   It was all the agents wanted to know. U.S. officials had been
pressing Mexican police to find the student. Tourism from across
the border had diminished since Kilroy vanished; the case had top
priority.
   Police rounded up the suspects at the ranch and found more than
200 pounds of marijuana, but that was not what made headlines.
   In the shed was a copper caldron. In it were the remnants of a
fire and something that looked like brains. Nearby were candles and
pots containing heads of black goats and roosters.
   The four suspects led police to shallow graves where the bodies
were buried. Sergio Martinez, who volunteered information on a 13th
victim, sweated for almost two hours digging up the body Thursday
as police ignored his pleas for water.
   At Miss Aldrete's home agents found more indications of black
magic. There was a list of names with pins next to some of them.
One agent said bloodstained children's clothing was found.
   The shack was immediately dubbed the ``satanic chapel'' by
federal agents and local newspapers. Those arrested became
``Satan's children'' and ``the narco-devils.''
   Each defendant faces a maximum sentence of 147 years.
   A wave of horror swept over the community because of the crimes,
even though drug smuggling and violence are well-known in this
swashbuckling border area and smugglers' exploits are the subjects
of popular ballads.
   To many in Matamoros, a city of nearly 500,000, the slayings
were a perversion of the traditional image of the Mexican smuggler
who helped the town, sent his kids to the best schools and was
often a heavy contributor to charity and civic causes.
   People were quick to point out that the ringleader was Cuban and
that the cult bore resemblances to ``santeria,'' a Caribbean
Hispanic version of voodoo, although anthropologists said it was
actually a mixed bag. Ripping out a living person's heart, for
instance, was an ancient Aztec rite.
   ``Our smugglers do not pray to the devil,'' said one resident,
Ala Rosa Garza. ``This (witchcraft and drugs) is something
imported. It is the American influence.''
</TEXT>
