<FIRST>r i AM-StadiumCollapse-Scene     04-15 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stadium Collapse-Scene,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheers of Fans Turn To Screams In Britain's Worst Sport Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stadium Collapse, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the bright sunshine of early
spring, the cheers of English soccer fans turned to screams as a
surging crowd crushed 93 spectators to death Saturday.
   Some of the victims at the Hillsborough Stadium in Sheffield
were taken away on advertising billboards used as makeshift
stretchers. Others lay motionless on the field while emergency
medical teams tried desperately to save their lives.
   One survivor numbed with shock sat in a corner of the stadium,
head in his hands.
   All around him, police gathered up clothing and belongings as
ambulances sped across the green turf, picking up bodies and taking
the injured to hospitals.
   One doctor told of ``sheer mayhem'' when he ran to help the
dying.
   ``There was one chap I went to who was clinically dead,'' Dr.
Glyn Phillips said. ``He had no heartbeat.''
   Phillips said he managed to resuscitate the fan, but ``I don't
know what the state of his cerebral function is going to be.''
   The disaster occurred when the 54,000-capacity stadium was
almost full. Police said they opened the gate to admit other fans,
fearing if they didn't there might be trouble outside.
   The move proved fatal. Inside, hundreds of spectators were
pushed against a steel mesh anti-riot fence that soon collapsed.
   ``It seemed as if it was four deep in dead bodies with people
climbing over them,'' said 22-year-old Stuart McGeagh.
   Another survivor, Gary Stanley, 20, said crowd control outside
the stadium was ``crazy.''
   ``There was complete madness and somehow the doors were
opened,'' he said. ``There were too many people in the section and
I saw some people crushed against barriers. The arrangements were
dreadful and I've still got a full ticket. I didn't even have to
show it to get in.''
   Another Liverpool fan, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said: ``It was ridiculous. They just opened the gates and waved
them in. I have two friends but I don't know what's happened to
them.
   ``I was crushed up to one of the railings and got cuts to my arm
but I was lucky to get out alive.''
   As police cleared the ground, fans wandered around aimlessly.
Huge sections of the fence had been ripped away; one section was
bent out of shape like a pipe cleaner.
   ``People were just crushing in,'' one fan told Yorkshire
television. ``There was a lad and his girlfriend and they were just
screaming. His words were `please God, help me,' and I believe the
girl died. Her face was just blue.''
</TEXT>
