<FIRST>r a AM-Drugs-Prison     04-15 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Prison,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Drop Plan for D.C.-Area Prison as Part of Anti-Drug Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUMBERLAND, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans for a new federal prison in the
Washington D.C. area _ a major part of national drug czar William
Bennett's announced crackdown on crime in the nation's capital _
have been shelved in favor of building another prison in western
Maryland, officials said Saturday.
   ``It is no longer necessary that a facility be built in the
immediate Baltimore-Washington area. The capacity can be gained
more quickly in other ways,'' John Walters, chief of staff for
Bennett's National Office of Drug Control Policy, said Saturday.
   Bennett on Monday proposed a 700-bed Washington-area prison for
drug offenders when he unveiled plans to combat the epidemic of
drug-related violence in the nation's capital.
   ``The perception that initially came out was that there was
going to be this one facility to house all drug traffickers coming
out of the District of Columbia. It was a misunderstanding,'' said
Greg Bogdan, public information officer for the U.S. Bureau of
Prisons.
   On Friday, U.S. Bureau of Prisons Director J. Michael Quinlan
said $50 million had been earmarked to build a medium-security
prison and a minimum-security prison camp about five miles south of
Cumberland. The prison complex, housing at least 700 prisoners, is
slated for completion in the fall of 1991.
   Bennett spokesman Don Hamilton said Saturday the Cumberland
facility essentially would replace plans for the Washington-area
prison. ``As a result of the D.C. initiative a prison that was
going to be built someday is going to be built in Cumberland,'' he
said.
   Under the plan announced by Bennett, the federal Bureau of
Prisons will immediately accept 250 prisoners housed in the local
jail, a 500-bed pre-trial detention center is to be built within a
year, and a 700-bed prison was to be built in the
Washington-Baltimore area.
   Additional personnel also were to be provided for drug-fighting
efforts under the plan, which Bennett said would cost $70 to $80
million. The 700-bed prison was the most costly part of the plan at
about $50 million.
