<HEAD>New Jersey Assembly To Investigate Elizabeth Layoffs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican gubernatorial hopeful and
the city's Democratic mayor engaged in a political shoving match
Saturday to lay blame for layoffs that cut the city's police and
fire departments by 20 percent.
   Meanwhile, ``morale is at an all time low,'' said Fire Chief
William Neafsey.
   ``Most of them are confused, frustrated and mad,'' Neafsey said
of his workers. ``You name the negative emotion, they have it.''
   Many police officers were wearing black bands around their
badges in honor of laid-off colleagues, said Police Director Joseph
Brennan.
   Chuck Hardwick, the Assembly speaker who is seeking the
Republican nomination for governor, said he would convene an
emergency task force to investigate the finances of Elizabeth and
other communities that have asked for more state money.
   Thomas Dunn, Elizabeth's mayor for a quarter-century, has blamed
the city's budget woes on Hardwick, who has blocked an Assembly
vote on a tax package that would provide $65 million more to
distressed cities.
   Dunn on Friday laid off 67 police officers, 53 firefighters, 24
emergency medical technicians and 81 other city workers.
   ``If New Jersey were a business and the city of Elizabeth one of
its departments, Mayor Dunn would be fired,'' Hardwich said during
a news conference. ``In my opinion, he's acted with a callous
disregard for public safety.''
   Hardwick said he wanted to know why Dunn had not used the $7.1
million in distressed-cities aid released by the state to Elizabeth
last week.
   ``He's a trickster ... he's a carnival showman,'' Dunn responded
from his office at City Hall. ``I welcome him and anybody else (to
investigate), including the attorney general.
   ``How can I spend cash that I don't have,'' he said. Dunn said
the $7.1 million has been promised but not paid. ``Even if I got
it, it wouldn't be enough. ... I need $26 million more.''
   The city council last week transferred $2.1 million from the
city's garbage disposal account to prevent the layoffs, but Dunn
has said that under state law, the money cannot be switched.
