<FIRST>r a AM-NorthropWhistleblower     04-15 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrop Whistleblower,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Northrop Worker Appalled By Shoddy Work On Cruise Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northrop division that made electronic
guidance components for cruise missiles was a place where getting
along meant going along with incompetence and shoddy work, a former
employee says.
   Florence Castaneda was one of three former Northrop employees
whose repeated complaints finally got the attention of federal
investigators, resulting in charges filed last week.
   She said she was motivated by her worries over nuclear weapons
with bad guidance systems which ``could be the start of World War
III,'' the Los Angeles Times reported Saturday.
   Castaneda, a senior assembler technician certified by the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration for a variety of
electronics work, said her struggle has left her feeling alienated
and mistrustful of the aerospace industry.
   From the day she started work at Northrop's Western Services
Department in El Monte in October 1983, Castaneda said she was
appalled.
   She saw employees in an electronics ``clean room'' smoking
cigarettes, eating lunch at work stations and watching soap operas
on televisions, she told the Times.
   Northrop Corp. and five current and former employees were
indicted Tuesday on charges of conspiring to defraud the government
in assembling part of the Air Force's cruise missile guidance
system and a component for the Navy's Harrier jet fighter.
   Northrop spokesman Tony Cantafio said Saturday that the company
acted on complaints about the plant two years ago.
   ``We fired the plant manager and three other employees in
1987,'' Cantafio said. ``And in December '87, we shut the plant
down. That is action that we took when it came to our attention.''
   The indictment charged that Northrop and the five, including
Castaneda's boss, conspired to install parts for the cruise missile
Flight Data Transmitter that failed to meet government
specifications.
   The terrain-hugging cruise missile, one of the most versatile
weapons in the U.S. arsenal, is capable of carrying either a
conventional or nuclear warhead.
   Castaneda said she began by complaining to her superior, Charles
Gonsalves, one of those who was fired and who was named in the
Tuesday indictment. Among her complaints was the lack of coding for
component wires, a standard procedure in the aerospace industry to
trace their origin.
   ``When I started to raise concerns, Mr. Gonsalves told me that
if I just did my work like everybody else, we would get along,''
Castaneda told the Times.
   But a nephew in the Air National Guard arranged a meeting with
agents from the Air Force's Office of Special Investigations,
Castaneda said. She invited fellow workers Leocadio Barajas and
Patricia Meyer.
   Barajas later was fired after confronting Gonsalves, and he and
Meyer eventually joined in a lawsuit against Northrop, alleging the
firm had defrauded the government by improperly testing the missile
parts. The Justice Department later joined the suit.
   Castaneda went on temporary disability from Northrop in April
1985 because of stress and a back injury.
   Castaneda told the Times a psychologist was assigned to her
through Northrop's insurance adjuster, but his message was ``to
forgive Northrop and to forgive Mr. Gonsalves _ to ask God to
forgive them _ and to just go back to work,'' she said.
   Castaneda left Northrop for good in April 1987.
</TEXT>
