<SECOND>AM-Tanker-Oregon,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portland Says Exxon Valdez Will Arrive For inspection</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY CARPENTER HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Port of Portland announced Friday that
the damaged supertanker Exxon Valdez would arrive within six weeks
for inspection if state environmental officials allow it.
   The ship could arrive from May 15 to June 1, said port spokesman
Dick Montgomery, but the state Department of Environmental Quality
has the authority to reject the supertanker.
   The agency will decide after an inspection by a naval architect
who left for Alaska Friday afternoon, said spokeswoman Carolyn
Young.
   The tanker certainly would be rejected if it trailed ``any
significant oil'' while under tow, she said.
   Exxon Shipping Co. President Frank Iarossi has insisted the
vessel won't trail oil.
   Gregg Kantor, a spokesman for Oregon Gov. Neil Goldschmidt, said
the governor was unlikely to comment until after state officials
make their final decision on whether to let the ship dock in
Portland.
   Port officials have been lured to the repair job by the $20
million price tag and the prospect of hundreds of jobs.
   The Valdez is undergoing temporary repairs off the Alaskan
coast. The supertanker struck a reef in Prince William Sound on
March 24, spilling 10.1 million gallons of oil and fouling hundreds
of miles of beaches.
