<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Glance     04-15 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Glance,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of the budget agreement
for fiscal 1990 announced Friday by President Bush and
congressional leaders:
   _Totals: $1.2 trillion in spending, $1.1 trillion in revenues,
$99.4 billion deficit. The budget Bush proposed in February had
similar spending and revenue totals and estimated a $91.1 billion
deficit.
   _New tax revenue: $5.8 billion. Of the total, $5.3 billion will
be from taxes Congress and Bush will have to agree to, and $500
million will be from increased enforcement by the Internal Revenue
Service. Bush proposed $5.3 billion in this category.
   _Other revenues: $2.7 billion by increasing fees for federal
services, such as national park entrance fees, $5.7 billion by
selling as yet unspecified federal assets. Bush proposed a total of
$4.7 billion.
   _Military: $299.2 billion, down from Bush's $300.6 billion
request.
   _Entitlement programs: $556.4 billion in spending for programs
in which benefits are paid automatically to people who qualify,
$6.8 billion less than expected growth. Reductions include $2.7
billion from Medicare, $1.9 billion in farm payments and $1.1
billion from Postal Service and federal pension changes. Bush asked
for $537.3 billion.
   _Other domestic programs: $181.3 billion, $4.5 billion above
Bush's proposal and $300 million less than expected growth.
   _International affairs: $17 billion, down from Bush's $17.4
billion request.
   _Interest payments on the national debt: $181 billion, the same
as in Bush's budget.
   All figures are from the text of the agreement as calculated by
the Congressional Budget Office, or from Bush's proposed budget.
</TEXT>
