<FIRST>r a PM-People-Bush     04-15 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Bush,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>President, Mitterrand To Speak At Boston University Commencement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston University says it has the ``commencement
of the year'' _ President Bush and French President Francois
Mitterrand are scheduled to address the graduating class on May 21.
   Bush and Mitterrand will receive honorary degrees at the
school's 150th commencement, university officials said Thursday.
Barbara Bush also will attend the ceremony.
   University President John Silber, a conservative Democrat,
invited Bush and Mitterrand. School spokesman Tom Cashman said
Silber and Bush have been friends since the 1960s, when Bush was a
congressman from Texas and Silber was a professor of philosophy at
the University of Texas. Cashman said Silber also has been friendly
with Mitterrand for a number of years.
   ``It's certainly the commencement of the year,'' Cashman said.
``We're very pleased because it comes at such a pivotal time for
the university.''
   After Mitterrand told Bush he had accepted Silber's invitation,
Bush invited Mitterrand to spend that weekend at his home in
Kennebunkport, Maine.
   From Maine, the two leaders plan to travel together for the
commencement, the university said.
   Bush also is scheduled to deliver graduation speeches at Texas A
&amp; M on May 12, Alcorn State University and Mississippi State
University on May 13 and the U.S. Coast Guard Academy on May 24.
</TEXT>
