<FIRST>r a PM-SpellingBee     04-15 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spelling Bee,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Spelling Bee Judgment Is A-F-F-I-R-M-E-D</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court has upheld a ruling
against a man who claimed his son was cheated out of a 1987
spelling bee championship.
   ``As for the judgment of the trial court,'' appellate Judge
Arthur Gilbert ruled Wednesday, ``we'll spell it out:
A-F-F-I-R-M-E-D.''
   Leonard McDonald of Thousand Oaks claimed his son Gavin, then
13, lost the Ventura County Spelling Bee because two students,
instead of one, from Los Altos School in Camarillo were allowed by
the sponsoring Ventura Star-Free Press to advance in the contest.
   In the Camarillo contest, student Victor Wang had spelled
H-O-R-S-Y and Steven Chen had spelled it H-O-R-S-E-Y.
   Although judges ruled that Steven won, Star-Free Press officials
said an unacceptable dictionary had been used. A tie was declared
because Webster's Third New International Dictionary said both
spellings were correct. Both Victor and Steven were allowed to go
on to the countywide competition where Steven beat Gavin in the
27th round.
   Gavin's father argued that Steven shouldn't have been allowed to
compete in the county finals and asked for $2 million in damages.
In his lawsuit McDonald named the newspaper, the paper's editor at
the time and Scripps Howard newspaper group, which runs the
national spelling bee in Washington.
   McDonald contended his son suffered unfair treatment that caused
him to lose his standing in the community and suffer ``humiliation,
indignity, grief, fright and mental anguish.''
   Ventura County Superior Court Judge Kenneth Yegan dismissed the
case in November 1987. But the case was appealed.
   Gilbert, in upholding Yegan's action, called the lawsuit
frivolous and said the reason Gavin lost was that he finally
misspelled a word.
   ``Gavin took first place in his school and can be justifiably
proud of his performance,'' Gilbert wrote. ``It is this lawsuit
that is trivial, not his achievement. Our courts try to give
redress for real harms; they cannot offer palliatives for imagined
injuries.''
   John Bowman, editor of the Star-Free Press, said he was pleased
the matter was resolved.
</TEXT>
