<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 0240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CivilRights     04-15 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Civil Rights,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liberal Black Congressman Endorses Lucas to Head Justice Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of William Lucas to head the
Justice Department's civil rights division were given a boost when
a liberal Michigan congressman endorsed the Republican, a fellow
black from Detroit.
   Rep. John Conyers, joining the debate over Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh's choice of Lucas, on Friday urged President Bush to
expedite the nomination.
   Conyers' endorsement may blunt the potential effect of the 68-2
vote the Detroit NAACP took last Monday to oppose Lucas, whose
nomination has not been formally announced by Bush.
   Coupled with a decision Wednesday night by the Detroit Urban
League to endorse Lucas, Conyers' support could head off additional
opposition.
   Other civil rights groups, while privately expressing
reservations about Lucas, have withheld public comment, perhaps to
assess the political climate on Capitol Hill.
   Conyers, a Democrat, took issue with statements by civil rights
leaders that Lucas lacks the necessary experience for the job.
   ``Experience is not the issue in the Lucas appointment,''
Conyers said in a statement. ``The most important issue is the
nominee's commitment to civil rights enforcement and affirmative
action.''
   ``After eight years of William Bradford Reynolds at the helm of
the civil rights division, Bill Lucas will be a breath of fresh
air,'' Conyers said.
   ``I believe he is qualified to do the job,'' Conyers said. ``I
am confident of his commitment to moving the federal government
back into being an advocate for civil rights.''
   Civil rights groups have questioned Lucas' qualifications for
the job, noting his lack of experience in the civil rights movement.
   Lucas, a former sheriff and later chief executive of Waymally
submitted by Bush, is subject to Senate confirmation.
   Lucas ran as the GOP's unsuccessful candidate for Michigan
governor in 1968. His choice as civil rights chief is seen by
political observers as part of the Republican Party's efforts to
attract more black voters.
   Critics who have questioned Lucas' commitment to civil rights
noted his statements on affirmative action.
   His record as sheriff has also been cited by opponents, who
point out he was cited for contempt of court in 1976 for failing to
reduce overcrowding in the Wayne County Jail when he was sheriff.
</TEXT>
