<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BeeMites     04-15 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bee Mites,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Cites Lack of Support in Canceling Quarantine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says widespread
opposition in the honeybee industry prompted it to cancel a planned
quarantine of states where a parasitic mite is plaguing apiaries.
   The proposal would have applied to 19 states, the District of
Columbia and 15 U.S. territories or other possessions known or
believed to be infested with the Varroa mite. Public comments were
solicited through March 31.
   ``The comments we have received indicate widespread opposition
to the proposed Varroa mite program,'' James W. Glosser,
administrator of the department's Animal and Plant Health
Inspection Service, said Friday.
   ``Without extensive support from the affected groups, a federal
effort to retard the spread of Varroa cannot work,'' he said.
   Under the proposed quarantine, the interstate movement of
honeybees and bee equipment would have been restricted. Such
articles would have required inspection and, or, treatment before
being allowed to move across state lines.
   Varroa mites were discovered in the United States in a Wisconsin
apiary in September 1987. The USDA imposed a quarantine in April
1988 but was canceled after a month because it was too complex to
administer.
   The mite is an external parasite of adult honeybees and their
developing larvae, or brood. Infestations cause decreased brood
numbers, deformed bees and weaken the bees' ability to pollinate
plants and produce honey.
</TEXT>
