<TEXT>
   A supermarket tabloid has paid $60,000 to
publish the first excerpts of an unauthorized biography of
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
   The weekly Star said the first of five parts from ``A Woman
Called Jackie,'' by C. David Heymann, will be on supermarket racks
Monday. The other excerpts will run on consecutive Mondays.
   The Star reported in its April 18 edition that the excerpts will
include disclosures about alleged amphetamine use by President
Kennedy and his wife, and a phone call by Marilyn Monroe to Mrs.
Kennedy at the White House.
   Book sales begin May 2. The New York Daily News, Cosmopolitan,
New Woman and McCall's have second serialization rights, USA Today
reported.
   Mrs. Kennedy had no comment, according to her spokeswoman, Nancy
Tuckerman.
