<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:HelloHollywood Adv17   04-15 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Hello Hollywood, Adv 17,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday AMs, April 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Goodbye Hollywood; Hello Dino</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1906 earthquake has shattered San
Francisco nearly 7,000 times, floods have destroyed a warring
planet and ostrich-plumed showgirls have paraded down the grand
staircase on the world's largest stage.
   But after 11 years of pleasing the crowds at Ballys, ``Hello
Hollywood, Hello'' is saying goodbye to make way for Dino, Liza and
Frank.
   ``It's a wonderful, wonderful show, but it's run 11 years and in
the last couple of years the audience has been down. Our surveys
showed that people wanted to see name stars,'' said Richard Sturm,
vi entertainment at Bally's hotel-casinos.
   Dean Martin will inaugurate the new policy April 27, after the
show's last performance April 18. Martin will be followed by Paul
Anka, Barbara Mce president forandrell, Liza Minnelli, Barry Manilow and
Frank
Sinatra.
   ``It will be a real sadness,'' said Diane Petersen, a principal
singer who has been with the show since it opened June 2, 1978.
   ``That's always a difficult part of our business. You become so
close to people, then face the reality that you've got to go other
directions.''
   Michael Eardley, a principal singer who also has been with the
show from its opening, echoed the spirit of family in the 90-membere.
   The waterfalls weigh six tons each. Another set weighs 10 tons.
   The stage, built solely to accommodate ``Hello Hollywood,'' is
58 feet shorter than a football field and 180 feet wide. Three
giant elevators descend into a basement below for scene changes.
   Sturm said Bally's was not ruling out the possibility of future
productions in Reno, and that there has been talk of selling
``Hello Hollywood'' _ earthquakes, waterfalls and all _ if a buyer
comes along.
   Greg Glodowski, a principal dancer who moved here nine years ago
from the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater, said the area will lose a
valuable pool of talent when the show closes. He will stay in Reno
to work as an attorney specializing in tax matters, and will dance
with the local ballet company.
   Eardley and his dancer-wife, Katherine, who met 4{ years ago on
the ``Hello Hollywood'' stage, run a recording studio and music
production company.
   Petersen is considering public relations work so she can remain
in the Reno area if another performing opportunity doesn't come
along.
   ``Hello Hollywood'' was developed around a motion picture theme
when the casino was the MGM Grand, and the scenes remained after
Bally's bought it three years ago.
   Eardley said it is essentially the same show as when it opened,
a sameness that challenges the performers to keep their scenes
fresh.
   ``You may be bored or sick as a dog and not feel like singing a
love song, but this is a business like any other and you call upon
your technique and discipline and that's what gets you through,''
he said.
   ``You know that most of the people out there are seeing it for
the first time,'' Peterson said. ``They're going to see it one
time, so you want to be the best that you can be.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
