<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv17 1stLd-Writethru 04-15 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 17, 1st Ld-Writethru,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, April 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Conflicting Corporate Debt Ratings: Whom To Believe?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, For example ..., to CORRECT to $3.9 billion sted
$3.9 million; picks up 10th graf, Similarly, some ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The quality of corporate debt improved in the
first quarter. The quality of corporate debt deteriorated in the
first quarter.
   Which you believe depends on which of the two major bond-rating
services you listen to.
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. says the quality of corporate credit, as
determined by the company's ratings of debt issues, improved in the
January-March period.
   Moody's Investors Service, the other major debt-rating service,
says that corporate credit quality continued its downward trend,
due mainly to buyouts, restructurings and stock buybacks that
affect corporate debt levels.
   For the quarter, S&amp;P says it upgraded the ratings of 88 debt
issues representing about $63 billion in debt, while it downgraded
64 issues representing about $30 billion. The number it upgraded
was about 1.3 times the number it downgraded.
   Moody's says it upgraded 32 companies representing $33 billion
debt, while it downgraded 66 totaling $47 billion. Moody's
downgrade-to-upgrade ratio was 2.1-to-1.
   One of the reasons for the vastly different snapshots of
first-quarter debt quality is the timing of when the two ratings
services upgrades or downgrades various debt issues.
   ``There may be leads and lags,'' said John Lonski, Moody's
senior economist.
   For example, Moody's upgraded $3.9 billion in USX Corp. debt
last September. S&amp;P didn't make a similar upgrade, involving $5
billion in USX debt, until the first quarter, thus accounting for
some of the difference in the overall quarterly ratings improvement
noted by S&amp;P.
   Similarly, some of the bonds Moody's downgraded during the
quarter may have been downgraded earlier by S&amp;P.
   ``As far as we're concerned, the first quarter had twice as many
downgrades as upgrades,'' Lonski said last week.
   Kenneth C. Pfeil, a senior vice president at S&amp;P, agreed that
the timing of ratings changes was a factor in the differing
interpretations of how debt fared in the first quarter.
   Another reason could be the subjective factor inherent in debt
rating. Rating are not based entirely on hard numbers; in part,
they reflect a judgment call on how a company's expected courses of
action will affect its debt. Because of this variable, the ratings
of the two services can differ.
   But Pfeil added that he believes his firm's first-quarter
ratings picture is a fluke in an otherwise downward trend of
corporate debt quality.
   Since 1982, he said, there have been only three other quarters
where S&amp;P's upgrades exceeded downgrades, he said.
   ``After this quarter, we'll probably see the downgrades overtake
the upgrades again. I don't think we've broken the trend,'' he said.
   A company's debt rating is important because it can affect the
price of the debt securities and the amount of interest a company
must pay on new debt issues in order to entice investors to buy
them.
   For example, when a company's debt rating drops, it may find
that it has to offer a higher interest rate on any new issues,
making them more expensive.
   Lonski said that though Moody's believes the overall quality of
corporate debt deteriorated in the first quarter, it actually
improved slightly from the last quarter of 1988, when Moody's had
57 downgrades to 25 upgrades, for a downgrade-to-upgrade ratio of
2.3.
   About half the Moody's downgrades in the first quarter reflected
the continued concern by the credit rating companies about the
effects of corporate takeovers and restructuring, Lonski said.
   When one company takes over another through a leveraged buyout,
it typically takes on a huge chunk of debt from the loans and
credit-market issues needed to pay for the acquisition.
   Such debt raises concerns about the ability of the company to
pay interest on its existing debt.
   For example, both ratings services downgraded the debt of RJR
Nabisco Inc. in the first quarter due to the $25 billion leveraged
buyout of the Atlanta-based food and tobacco giant.
   The other half of Moody's ratings downgrades during the quarter
reflect various factors, such as increases in corporate debt due to
other restructurings including stock buybacks, Lonski said.
   Lonski also wasn't optimistic about corporate credit quality
improving in the near future. He said he expects the wave of
corporate takeovers and restructurings involving debt to continue.
   ``We see no end to the situation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Monday, April 17</NOTE>
