<FIRST>a f BC-ChannelOne Adv17   04-15 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Channel One, Adv 17,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, April 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Channel One Test Enters Final Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Channel One commercial news program for
teens completes a test run this week, geography teacher Jim Peters
expects a planned series of reports on life in Japan will command
his class' attention.
   His seventh graders at Eisenhower Middle School in Kansas City,
Kan., were captivated in early March with a Channel One series on
Russian teen-agers and paid more than usual interest to his lesson
that week about the Soviet Union.
   ``Instead of some 40-year-old geography teacher telling them
what he saw when he went there, the show allowed the kids to see
something fresh for themselves every day,'' he said.
   Peters expressed hope that the reports on Japan will give an
educational boost to this week's lessons on that nation.
   Those are hopes shared by the Channel One developers, Whittle
Communications LP, which has visions of turning the test project
into its biggest commercial venture yet by taking it national in
the fall of 1990.
   The Knoxville, Tenn.-based media company has spent more than
$5.5 million on its Channel One test that began running in six
schools March 6. The costs including equipping each school with
about $50,000 in televisions and video equipment to receive the
daily 12-minutes news shows.
   But Whittle and school officials know that the project will not
win much support nationally if they can't show it helps educate
youngsters.
   That is one of the reasons that in each of the five weeks of the
test, Whittle sent teachers a course guide with suggested exercises
based on that week's program.
   Even as the 25th and last show signs off this Friday, Whittle's
task of evaluating whether the project should be expanded has only
begun.
   Ed Winter, the Whittle executive who has overseen the
development of Channel One, said that decision won't be made until
mid-summer.
   Before that, he plans intensive talks with administrators,
teachers, parents and students at each of the six schools in the
test. In addition to Kansas City, the schools are in Cerritos,
Calif.; Knoxville, Tenn.; Cincinnati; Billerica, Mass.; and Detroit.
   He will also be evaluating research designed to determine if the
program significantly improved students' knowledge of current
events.
   Tests will have been given to students at each of the test
schools as well as their sister schools which did not see the show.
   Researchers have also interviewed students on behalf of the
seven advertisers who bought part of the two minutes a day of
commercials carried on the show.
   The commercial involvement that has seen companies pitch jeans,
chewing gum, deodorant and candy to an audience of 10,000 teens has
drawn fierce attacks from children's advocates and educators
including the National Parent-Teachers Association.
   Patricia Albjerg Graham, dean of the Harvard School of Education
in Cambridge, Mass., said school officials should not be fooled
about Whittle's basic intentions. ``Whittle is doing this to make
money,'' she said.
   She said there is a potential danger in programs such as Channel
One for teachers to feel they can trim their lesson plans because a
topic may have already been covered on the news show.
   ``The danger is that you'll give them this icing on the cake and
never get on with the nutritious carbohydrates and the meat,'' she
said.
   She said while the test has probably done no harm to the
students and may have boosted their awareness of current events,
she said a longterm commitment to such programs could have
unfortunate consequences.
   Since students are required by law to attend school and schools
are hitting them with commercially-sponsored TV programs, she said
some students may conclude it is just as important to eat a certain
kind of fast food as it is to learn arithmetic.
   ``That is a subliminal message that is very bad for our
children,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, April 17 and thereafter</NOTE>
