<FIRST>a f BC-TradeDeficit Adv17   04-15 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Trade Deficit, Adv 17,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, April 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Will Shrink For All The Wrong Reasons</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Harald is cq in 14th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The good news is the trade deficit eventually
will shrink. The bad news is why.
   The next recession, which may come next year, will cause a
short, sharp and temporary improvement in the trade gap by
decreasing American demand for imported goods, economists say.
   Increased foreign ownership of American factories also will
shrink the deficit. That's because foreign companies will supply
the American market from factories here instead of by shipments
from abroad.
   A decline in the value of the dollar will make the deficit
smaller. But a cheaper dollar means Americans' money is worth less
in world markets and foreigners can buy U.S. assets at bargain
prices.
   Managed trade is touted in Washington as a way to close the
trade gap. But ``managing'' trade usually involves restricting or
taxing imports, which hurts people who buy things like
videocassette recorders.
   In summary, the four main factors that should eventually narrow
the trade deficit _ recession, foreign ownership, a cheaper dollar
and trade policy _ all carry big negatives.
   ``There is no free lunch. There's no solution that's going to
make everybody happy,'' Jeff Faux, president of the Economic Policy
Institute in Washington, said last week.
   The trade deficit has a good side: It means Americans are
consuming goods and services from abroad without being required to
pay for them with an equal amount of goods and services created in
the United States.
   But the foreigners are accumulating IOUs, and persistent trade
deficits have turned the United States into the world's largest
debtor.
   The stubbornness of the deficit was obvious last Friday when the
Commerce Department reported that March's deficit had jumped 20.9
percent to $10.5 billion.
   A fresh decline in the dollar undoubtedly would help shrink the
deficit somewhat, but U.S. policymakers are too aware of the ``good
news, bad news'' tradeoffs to favor sharp depreciation.
   The American economy, already running near full capacity, could
go into inflationary overheating if a dollar drop did stimulate
exports dramatically. Higher-priced imports would also add to
inflation.
   Moreover, a cheaper dollar would make it even easier for
Japanese, German, British and Canadian companies to buy American
assets, ranging from Treasury bonds to hotels and factories.
   ``I have some Japanese clients who are very eager to have the
yen go higher because they want to transplant to the United States
and they want to do it cheaper,'' said Harald Malmgren, an economic
consultant in Washington.
   Malmgren said he was convinced that American imports of cars
from Japan will virtually cease within three years because of North
American production by the Japanese automakers. The U.S. plants
will even export cars to Europe, Latin America and Japan.
   The good news on trade is bad news for Detroit. The Big Three
automakers will have a hard time competing with the modern U.S.
factories of Honda, Nissan, Toyota and the rest.
   One neglected cause of the trade deficit is the durable demand
for dollars by foreign central banks, which use the U.S. currency
the way they once used gold, as a reserve to back their own
currencies.
   The dollars that Americans spend on foreign goods are finding
their way into the vaults of foreign central banks instead of
coming back to the United States through purchases of American
goods.
   A trade deficit is thus the unavoidable consequence of the
appetite for dollars by foreign central banks, said John Mueller,
chief economist of Bell Mueller Cannon Inc.
   The good side of that bad news is that the IOUs held by the
foreign banks may never be cashed in, Mueller said. ``In effect
they are permanent holders of dollars. They will be permanent
loans.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, April 17</NOTE>
